{"title_page": "David Anthony Kraft", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox comics creator\n| name          = David Anthony Kraft\n| image         = <!-- Only freely-licensed images may be used to depict living people.  See [[WP:NONFREE]].  -->\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1952}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| area          = Critic, writer\n| alias         = DAK, Dave the Dude\n| notable works = ''Comics Interview'',<br />''[[The Defenders (comic book)|The Defenders]]''\n| awards        = \n}}\n'''David Anthony Kraft''' pretty cool feller\n\n== Writing career ==\nBefore his comics career, Kraft worked as a [[Music journalism|rock and roll journalist]].<ref name=\"DragonCon\">{{cite web |url= http://www.dragoncon.org/dc_guest_detail.php?id=1734 |title= David Anthony Kraft|year= 2007|publisher= [[Dragon Con]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110520114420/http://www.dragoncon.org/dc_guest_detail.php?id=1734|archivedate=May 20, 2011 |url-status= dead|df=mdy-all|accessdate= August 17, 2008}}</ref> In September 1976, he became editor of ''[[FOOM]]'' with issue #15,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://samruby.com/Series/FOOM/foom15.htm|title= ''FOOM'' #15|first= Sam|last= Ruby|date= Fall 1976|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100131175657/http://samruby.com/Series/FOOM/foom15.htm|archivedate=January 31, 2010|url-status= dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Marvel's self-produced [[fan magazine]], lasting as editor until the magazine's final issue (#22) in 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://samruby.com/Series/FOOM/foom22.htm|title= ''FOOM'' #22|first= Sam|last= Ruby|date= Fall 1978|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120218150628/http://samruby.com/Series/FOOM/foom22.htm|archivedate=February 18, 2012|url-status= dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nKnown for his offbeat approach, Kraft first made a name for himself as a comic book author with his work on [[Marvel Comics]]' ''[[The Defenders (comic book)|The Defenders]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|last = DeAngelo|first = Daniel|title = The Not-Ready-For-Super-Team Players A History of the Defenders|magazine = [[Back Issue!]]|issue = 65|pages = 9\u201311|publisher = [[TwoMorrows Publishing]]|date = July 2013|location= Raleigh, North Carolina}}</ref> particularly the 1977 \"Scorpio Saga\" story-arc (issues #46, 48\u201350).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/study/4273/saga/def_scorp.html|title= Who Remembers Scorpio?|first= D. K.|last= Latta |publisher= The Masked Bookwyrm|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20061113140151/http://www.geocities.com/soho/study/4273/saga/def_scorp.html|archivedate=November 13, 2006 |url-status= dead|df=mdy-all|accessdate= August 15, 2008}}</ref> In ''The Defenders'', Kraft wrestled with large philosophical issues: the temptations of power, the Cold War and nuclear power, sibling rivalry, and growing old alone. Kraft also merged his interests in music and comics by inserting multiple references to the band [[Blue \u00d6yster Cult]] into his ''Defenders'' stories specifically the \"Xenogenesis:  Day of the Demons\" storyline, issues #58\u201360.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://members.aol.com/bocfaqman/boc_faq.html|title= Blue \u00d6yster Cult FAQ|first= John|last= Swartz|date= December 10, 2001|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070209142407/http://members.aol.com/bocfaqman/boc_faq.html|archivedate=February 9, 2007 |url-status= dead|df=mdy-all|accessdate= September 17, 2008|quote= References to Blue Oyster Cult songs are sprinkled throughout the \"Xenogenesis:  Day of the Demons\" storyline in Marvel's ''The Defenders'' comic. The issues are Vol.1, 58\u201360 dated April, May and June 1978. The story is by David Anthony Kraft and the first comic in the trilogy is \"Dedicated to Eric Bloom and BOC!\"}}</ref> Kraft combined music and comics in his scripting of the ''[[Marvel Comics Super Special|Marvel Super Special]]'' #4 featuring [[The Beatles]].<ref name=\"DragonCon\" /> ''Marvel Super Special'' #7, an adaptation of the film ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band (film)|Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'', by Kraft and artists [[George P\u00e9rez]] and [[Jim Mooney]] was promoted on the \"[[Bullpen Bulletins]]\" page in Marvel Comics cover-dated January 1979. It was [[List of comics solicited but never published|never published]] in the U.S. \"because the book was late and the movie proved to be a commercial failure,\" according to a contemporaneous news account.<ref>{{cite journal|title= The Sgt. Pepper Snafu|journal= [[The Comics Journal]]|issue= 44|page= 12|publisher= Fantagraphics Books|date= January 1979|location= Stamford, Connecticut<!--location in 1979-->}}</ref>\n\nKraft wrote the [[John Jameson (comics)|Man-Wolf]] feature in ''[[Tower of Shadows#Creatures on the Loose|Creatures on the Loose]]'' and ''[[Marvel Premiere]]'' and featured the character in ''[[The Spectacular Spider-Man]] Annual'' #3 (1981).<ref>{{cite book|last = Manning|first = Matthew K.|last2= Gilbert|first2= Laura, ed.|chapter= 1980s|title = Spider-Man Chronicle Celebrating 50 Years of Web-Slinging|publisher= [[Dorling Kindersley]]|year= 2012|location= London, United Kingdom|page = 121|isbn = 978-0756692360|quote= John Jameson and his werewolf alter ego Man-Wolf returned in this yarn by writer David Kraft and penciler Jim Sherman.}}</ref> He wrote the entire run, except the first issue, of ''[[She-Hulk|Savage She-Hulk]]'', which ran from 1980\u20131982. Kraft worked on such titles as ''[[Captain America]]'' and scripted the first story drawn by [[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]] for Marvel Comics: \"Dark Asylum,\" published in ''[[The Tomb of Dracula|Giant-Size Dracula]]'' #5 (June 1975).<ref>{{cite journal|last= Isabella|first= Tony|authorlink= Tony Isabella|title= Tony's Tips|journal= [[Comics Buyer's Guide]]|issue= 1433|publisher= [[Krause Publications]]|date= May 4, 2001|location= Iola, Wisconsin|url= http://www.worldfamouscomics.com/tony/back20010504.shtml|df=mdy-all|accessdate= September 17, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn the early to mid-1980s Kraft wrote children's storybooks featuring Marvel characters such as [[Spider-Man]], the [[Hulk]], and the [[Fantastic Four]] for the [[Children's Press]], [[Marvel Books]] and [[Simon & Schuster]].<ref name=\"DragonCon\" /> During this same time he wrote the interactive game books ''Ghost Knights of Camelot'' for Avon, and ''Robot Race'' for Scholastic books. In 1983\u20131984, Kraft wrote ''[[World's Finest Comics]]'' for [[DC Comics]],<ref>{{cite journal|last = Addiego|first = Frankie|title = The Final Days of ''World's Finest''|journal = Back Issue!|issue = 73|pages = 66\u201367|publisher = TwoMorrows Publishing|date = July 2014|location= Raleigh, North Carolina}}</ref> including that series' issue #300 (Feb. 1984).<ref>{{cite book|last=Manning|first= Matthew K.|last2=Dolan|first2=Hannah, ed.|chapter= 1980s|title = DC Comics Year By Year A Visual Chronicle|publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]]|year=2010|location= London, United Kingdom|isbn= 978-0-7566-6742-9 |page= 206|quote= In the tradition of DC's anniversary editions, ''World's Finest Comics'' #300 was an extra-length issue contributed to by a variety of comic book talent. Written by David Anthony Kraft, Mike W. Barr, and Marv Wolfman, and illustrated by Ross Andru, Mark Texeira, Sal Amendola, and George P\u00e9rez.}}</ref> After that, Kraft did occasional comics writing, but mostly focused his energies on publishing and criticism. In 1995, Kraft worked as story-editor and scripter for the short-lived animated series ''[[G.I. Joe Extreme]]''. Kraft is the co-writer and editor of ''Yi Soon Shin: Warrior and Defender'' by Onrie Kompan Productions, LLC.\n\n== Publisher, critic and literary agent ==\n\n=== Fictioneer Books ===\nIn 1974, Kraft founded the specialty science fiction publisher Fictioneer Books. Over the years, Fictioneer has published books by such authors as [[A. E. van Vogt]], [[Robert E. Howard]], [[Jack London]], [[Otis Adelbert Kline]], and [[Don McGregor]].<ref name=\"DragonCon\" />\n\nFictioneer and its imprint '''Comics Interview Group''' published magazines including ''David Anthony Kraft's Comics Interview'', trade journals such as ''Comics Revue'', and the trade text ''100 Hot Tips from Top Comics Creators'' (1994). In early 1985 Comics Interview Group branched out into comic books by taking on Henry and Audrey Vogel's ''[[Southern Knights]]'' (previously a self-published series). In 1986 they expanded their comics lineup with ''MICRA''  and ''Aristocratic Xtraterrestrial Time-Traveling Thieves'', and began publishing a number of ''Southern Knights'' reprints in the form of graphic novels, one-shots, and limited series. Though 1988 saw them also introduce [[Julie Woodcock]] and [[Brian Stelfreeze]]'s ''CyCops'', none of their comics publications sold as well as ''Southern Knights'', and by the end of that year they had stopped publishing any other titles. In mid-1989 ''Southern Knights'' was canceled as well, and the Comics Interview imprint was again devoted solely to magazines and trade publications although they would co-publish ''Southern Knights'' No. 35 and 36 in 1992.\n\n; Comics Interview\nIn 1983, Kraft founded ''David Anthony Kraft's Comics Interview'', with ran for 150 issues<ref>{{cite journal|title= Newswatch: ''Comics Interview'' Gives Up the Ghost|journal= [[The Comics Journal]]|issue= 183|page= 28|publisher= [[Fantagraphics Books]]|date= January 1996|location= Seattle, Washington}}</ref> between 1983 and 1995,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://comics.lib.msu.edu/rri/krri/kra.htm#kraftda |title=Index to the Comic Art Collection |publisher=[[Michigan State University Libraries]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5sbXKC3fK?url=http://comics.lib.msu.edu/rri/krri/kra.htm |archivedate=September 9, 2010 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and garnered [[Eisner Award|Eisner]] and [[Eagle Award (comics)|Eagle Award]] nominations. As suggested by the title, each issue of ''Comics Interview'' was filled entirely with in-depth creator interviews.\n\n=== Literary agent ===\nSince 1974, Kraft has been the [[literary agent]] for the estate of pulp author [[Otis Adelbert Kline]].\n\n==Influences and personal life==\nKraft counts science fiction author [[Leigh Brackett]], [[Stan Lee]], and writer [[E. Hoffmann Price]] as mentors.<ref name=\"DragonCon\" /> He currently lives in [[Clayton, Georgia]].{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n===Books===\n* ''Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band'' (Junior Press, 1979)\n* ''The Compleat OAK Leaves: Volume One of the Official Journal of Otis Adelbert Kline and his Works'' (editor) (Fictioneer Press, 1980)\n* ''Stan Lee Presents the Incredible Hulk'' pop-up book (Marvel Comics Group, 1980)\n* ''Captain America: The Secret Story of Marvel's Star-Spangled Super Hero'' (Children's Press, 1981)\n* ''The Fantastic Four: The Secret Story of Marvel's Cosmic Quartet'' (Children's Press, 1981)\n* ''The Incredible Hulk: The Secret Story of Marvel's Gamma-powered Goliath'' (Children's Press, 1981)\n* ''Attack of the Tarantula'' (Intervisual Communications, 1982)\n* ''The Dark Crystal'' (Marvel Books, 1982)\n* ''Stan Lee Presents the Incredible Hulk Pop-up Book, \"Trapped\"'' (Marvel Comics Group, 1982)\n* ''Fantastic Four vs. the Frightful Four'' coloring book (Marvel Books, 1983)\n* ''Heathcliff, #1 Cat at the Show''  coloring and activity book (Marvel Books, 1983)\n* ''Heathcliff at The Circus'' coloring book (Marvel Books, 1983)\n* ''The Treasure of Time'' (Marvel Books, 1983)\n* ''The Amazing Spider-Man: The Big Top Mystery'' (Marvel Books, 1984)\n* ''The Amazing Spider-Man and Wolverine in The Crime of the Centuries'' (Marvel Books, 1984)\n* ''Ghost Knights of Camelot'' (Avon Books, 1984) {{ISBN|978-0-380-89276-1}}\n* ''[[Micro Adventure]] no. 6: Robot Race'' (Scholastic, 1984) {{ISBN|0-590-33170-1}}\n* ''Marvel Super Heroes Secret Wars: Captain America and Iron Man in Escape from Doom'' (Budget Books, 1986)\n* ''Marvel Super Heroes Jumbo Coloring & Activity Book'' (Marvel Books, 1987)\n\n===Comic books===\n\n====Atlas/Seaboard Comics====\n* ''[[Demon Hunter (comics)|Demon Hunter]]'' #1 (1975)\n\n====DC Comics====\n* ''[[Blackhawk (DC Comics)|Blackhawk]]'' #247\u2013248 (1976)\n* ''[[Kamandi]], The Last Boy on Earth'' #44\u201346 (1976)\n* ''[[Richard Dragon]], Kung-Fu Fighter'' #11\u201312 (1976)\n* ''[[Secret Society of Super Villains]]'' #2\u20134 (1976)\n* ''[[Swamp Thing (comic book)|Swamp Thing]]'' #24 (1976)\n* ''[[Tarzan in comics|Tarzan]]'' #254 (1976)\n* ''[[World's Finest Comics]]'' #293, 295\u2013300, 302\u2013307 (1983\u20131984)\n\n====Marvel Comics====\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}} \n* ''[[Captain America (comic book)|Captain America]]'' #265\u2013266, 271, 273\u2013274 (1982)\n* ''[[Tower of Shadows|Creatures on the Loose]]'' #33\u201337 ([[John Jameson (comics)|Man-Wolf]]) (1975)\n* ''[[Defenders (comics)|Defenders]]'' #44\u201356, 58\u201368, 89 (1977\u20131980)\n* ''[[The Tomb of Dracula|Giant-Size Dracula]]'' #4\u20135 (1975)\n* ''Haunt of Horror'' #5 (1975)\n* ''[[The Rampaging Hulk|The Hulk]]'' #24 (1980)\n* ''[[Logan's Run (film)#Legacy|Logan's Run]]'' #2\u20135 (1977)\n* ''[[Marvel Comics Super Special]]'' #4 (''[[The Beatles|The Beatles Story]]'') (1978)\n* ''[[Marvel Fanfare]]'' #4, 17 (1982\u20131984)\n* ''[[Marvel Premiere]]'' #45\u201346 (1978\u20131979)\n* ''[[Marvel Preview]]'' #12\u201314 (1977\u20131978)\n* ''[[Marvel Spotlight]]'' #33 (1977)\n* ''Marvel Super Special'' #7 (''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band (film)|Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]''); #24 (''[[The Dark Crystal]]'') (1979\u20131983)\n* ''[[Marvel Super-Heroes (comics)|Marvel Super-Heroes]]'' vol. 2 #15 (1993)\n* ''[[Marvel Team-Up]]'' #109 (1981)\n* ''[[Marvel Two-in-One]]'' #41, 88\u201389, 94\u201395 (1978\u20131983)\n* ''[[Savage She-Hulk]]'' #2\u201325 (1980\u20131982)\n* ''[[The Spectacular Spider-Man]] Annual'' #3 (1981)\n* ''[[Tales of the Zombie]]'' #8 (1974)\n* ''[[Tarzan in comics|Tarzan]]'' #12, 15\u201321 (1978\u20131979)\n* ''[[Thor (Marvel Comics)|Thor]]'' #253 ([[Asgard (comics)|Tales of Asgard]] backup story) (1976)\n* ''[[What If (comics)|What If...?]]'' #37 (1983)\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{comicbookdb|type=creator|id=697|title=David Anthony Kraft}}\n* [http://www.mikesamazingworld.com/mikes/features/creator.php?creatorid=578 David Anthony Kraft] at Mike's Amazing World of Comics\n* [http://www.maelmill-insi.de/UHBMCC/namk17.htm#N354 David Anthony Kraft] at the Unofficial Handbook of Marvel Comics Creators\n* [http://joeguide.com/interviews/dak/entirelist.shtml Alphabetical index of the first 100 issues of ''Comics Interview''.]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[Defenders (comics)|The Defenders]]'' writer| before=[[Gerry Conway]]| after=[[Ed Hannigan]]| years=1977\u20131979}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[She-Hulk|Savage She-Hulk]]'' writer| before=[[Stan Lee]]| after= n/a| years=1980\u20131982}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[World's Finest Comics]]'' writer| before=[[Doug Moench]]| after=[[Kurt Busiek]]| years=1983\u20131984}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kraft, David Anthony}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:American comics writers]]\n[[Category:American magazine editors]]\n[[Category:American magazine publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:Comics critics]]\n[[Category:Literary agents]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics writers]]\n[[Category:People from Clayton, Georgia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox comics creator\n| name          = David Anthony Kraft\n| image         = <!-- Only freely-licensed images may be used to depict living people.  See [[WP:NONFREE]].  -->\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1952}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| area          = Critic, writer\n| alias         = DAK, Dave the Dude\n| notable works = ''Comics Interview'',<br />''[[The Defenders (comic book)|The Defenders]]''\n| awards        = \n}}\n'''David Anthony Kraft''' (born 1952)<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bailsprojects.com/(S(pz0nis55gdcxtz45absq5f55))/bio.aspx?Name=KRAFT%2c+DAVE|title= Kraft, Dave|first= Jerry|last= Bails|authorlink= Jerry Bails|date= n.d.|work= Who's Who of American Comic Books, 1928\u20131999|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170510111009/http://www.bailsprojects.com/%28S%28pz0nis55gdcxtz45absq5f55%29%29/bio.aspx?Name=KRAFT%2C+DAVE|archivedate= May 10, 2017|url-status= live|df= mdy-all}}</ref> also credited simply as '''David Kraft''', is an American comic book writer, publisher, and critic.  He is primarily known for his long-running journal of interviews and criticism, ''Comics Interview''.\n\n== Writing career ==\nBefore his comics career, Kraft worked as a [[Music journalism|rock and roll journalist]].<ref name=\"DragonCon\">{{cite web |url= http://www.dragoncon.org/dc_guest_detail.php?id=1734 |title= David Anthony Kraft|year= 2007|publisher= [[Dragon Con]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110520114420/http://www.dragoncon.org/dc_guest_detail.php?id=1734|archivedate=May 20, 2011 |url-status= dead|df=mdy-all|accessdate= August 17, 2008}}</ref> In September 1976, he became editor of ''[[FOOM]]'' with issue #15,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://samruby.com/Series/FOOM/foom15.htm|title= ''FOOM'' #15|first= Sam|last= Ruby|date= Fall 1976|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100131175657/http://samruby.com/Series/FOOM/foom15.htm|archivedate=January 31, 2010|url-status= dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Marvel's self-produced [[fan magazine]], lasting as editor until the magazine's final issue (#22) in 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://samruby.com/Series/FOOM/foom22.htm|title= ''FOOM'' #22|first= Sam|last= Ruby|date= Fall 1978|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120218150628/http://samruby.com/Series/FOOM/foom22.htm|archivedate=February 18, 2012|url-status= dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nKnown for his offbeat approach, Kraft first made a name for himself as a comic book author with his work on [[Marvel Comics]]' ''[[The Defenders (comic book)|The Defenders]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|last = DeAngelo|first = Daniel|title = The Not-Ready-For-Super-Team Players A History of the Defenders|magazine = [[Back Issue!]]|issue = 65|pages = 9\u201311|publisher = [[TwoMorrows Publishing]]|date = July 2013|location= Raleigh, North Carolina}}</ref> particularly the 1977 \"Scorpio Saga\" story-arc (issues #46, 48\u201350).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/study/4273/saga/def_scorp.html|title= Who Remembers Scorpio?|first= D. K.|last= Latta |publisher= The Masked Bookwyrm|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20061113140151/http://www.geocities.com/soho/study/4273/saga/def_scorp.html|archivedate=November 13, 2006 |url-status= dead|df=mdy-all|accessdate= August 15, 2008}}</ref> In ''The Defenders'', Kraft wrestled with large philosophical issues: the temptations of power, the Cold War and nuclear power, sibling rivalry, and growing old alone. Kraft also merged his interests in music and comics by inserting multiple references to the band [[Blue \u00d6yster Cult]] into his ''Defenders'' stories specifically the \"Xenogenesis:  Day of the Demons\" storyline, issues #58\u201360.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://members.aol.com/bocfaqman/boc_faq.html|title= Blue \u00d6yster Cult FAQ|first= John|last= Swartz|date= December 10, 2001|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070209142407/http://members.aol.com/bocfaqman/boc_faq.html|archivedate=February 9, 2007 |url-status= dead|df=mdy-all|accessdate= September 17, 2008|quote= References to Blue Oyster Cult songs are sprinkled throughout the \"Xenogenesis:  Day of the Demons\" storyline in Marvel's ''The Defenders'' comic. The issues are Vol.1, 58\u201360 dated April, May and June 1978. The story is by David Anthony Kraft and the first comic in the trilogy is \"Dedicated to Eric Bloom and BOC!\"}}</ref> Kraft combined music and comics in his scripting of the ''[[Marvel Comics Super Special|Marvel Super Special]]'' #4 featuring [[The Beatles]].<ref name=\"DragonCon\" /> ''Marvel Super Special'' #7, an adaptation of the film ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band (film)|Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'', by Kraft and artists [[George P\u00e9rez]] and [[Jim Mooney]] was promoted on the \"[[Bullpen Bulletins]]\" page in Marvel Comics cover-dated January 1979. It was [[List of comics solicited but never published|never published]] in the U.S. \"because the book was late and the movie proved to be a commercial failure,\" according to a contemporaneous news account.<ref>{{cite journal|title= The Sgt. Pepper Snafu|journal= [[The Comics Journal]]|issue= 44|page= 12|publisher= Fantagraphics Books|date= January 1979|location= Stamford, Connecticut<!--location in 1979-->}}</ref>\n\nKraft wrote the [[John Jameson (comics)|Man-Wolf]] feature in ''[[Tower of Shadows#Creatures on the Loose|Creatures on the Loose]]'' and ''[[Marvel Premiere]]'' and featured the character in ''[[The Spectacular Spider-Man]] Annual'' #3 (1981).<ref>{{cite book|last = Manning|first = Matthew K.|last2= Gilbert|first2= Laura, ed.|chapter= 1980s|title = Spider-Man Chronicle Celebrating 50 Years of Web-Slinging|publisher= [[Dorling Kindersley]]|year= 2012|location= London, United Kingdom|page = 121|isbn = 978-0756692360|quote= John Jameson and his werewolf alter ego Man-Wolf returned in this yarn by writer David Kraft and penciler Jim Sherman.}}</ref> He wrote the entire run, except the first issue, of ''[[She-Hulk|Savage She-Hulk]]'', which ran from 1980\u20131982. Kraft worked on such titles as ''[[Captain America]]'' and scripted the first story drawn by [[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]] for Marvel Comics: \"Dark Asylum,\" published in ''[[The Tomb of Dracula|Giant-Size Dracula]]'' #5 (June 1975).<ref>{{cite journal|last= Isabella|first= Tony|authorlink= Tony Isabella|title= Tony's Tips|journal= [[Comics Buyer's Guide]]|issue= 1433|publisher= [[Krause Publications]]|date= May 4, 2001|location= Iola, Wisconsin|url= http://www.worldfamouscomics.com/tony/back20010504.shtml|df=mdy-all|accessdate= September 17, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn the early to mid-1980s Kraft wrote children's storybooks featuring Marvel characters such as [[Spider-Man]], the [[Hulk]], and the [[Fantastic Four]] for the [[Children's Press]], [[Marvel Books]] and [[Simon & Schuster]].<ref name=\"DragonCon\" /> During this same time he wrote the interactive game books ''Ghost Knights of Camelot'' for Avon, and ''Robot Race'' for Scholastic books. In 1983\u20131984, Kraft wrote ''[[World's Finest Comics]]'' for [[DC Comics]],<ref>{{cite journal|last = Addiego|first = Frankie|title = The Final Days of ''World's Finest''|journal = Back Issue!|issue = 73|pages = 66\u201367|publisher = TwoMorrows Publishing|date = July 2014|location= Raleigh, North Carolina}}</ref> including that series' issue #300 (Feb. 1984).<ref>{{cite book|last=Manning|first= Matthew K.|last2=Dolan|first2=Hannah, ed.|chapter= 1980s|title = DC Comics Year By Year A Visual Chronicle|publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]]|year=2010|location= London, United Kingdom|isbn= 978-0-7566-6742-9 |page= 206|quote= In the tradition of DC's anniversary editions, ''World's Finest Comics'' #300 was an extra-length issue contributed to by a variety of comic book talent. Written by David Anthony Kraft, Mike W. Barr, and Marv Wolfman, and illustrated by Ross Andru, Mark Texeira, Sal Amendola, and George P\u00e9rez.}}</ref> After that, Kraft did occasional comics writing, but mostly focused his energies on publishing and criticism. In 1995, Kraft worked as story-editor and scripter for the short-lived animated series ''[[G.I. Joe Extreme]]''. Kraft is the co-writer and editor of ''Yi Soon Shin: Warrior and Defender'' by Onrie Kompan Productions, LLC.\n\n== Publisher, critic and literary agent ==\n\n=== Fictioneer Books ===\nIn 1974, Kraft founded the specialty science fiction publisher Fictioneer Books. Over the years, Fictioneer has published books by such authors as [[A. E. van Vogt]], [[Robert E. Howard]], [[Jack London]], [[Otis Adelbert Kline]], and [[Don McGregor]].<ref name=\"DragonCon\" />\n\nFictioneer and its imprint '''Comics Interview Group''' published magazines including ''David Anthony Kraft's Comics Interview'', trade journals such as ''Comics Revue'', and the trade text ''100 Hot Tips from Top Comics Creators'' (1994). In early 1985 Comics Interview Group branched out into comic books by taking on Henry and Audrey Vogel's ''[[Southern Knights]]'' (previously a self-published series). In 1986 they expanded their comics lineup with ''MICRA''  and ''Aristocratic Xtraterrestrial Time-Traveling Thieves'', and began publishing a number of ''Southern Knights'' reprints in the form of graphic novels, one-shots, and limited series. Though 1988 saw them also introduce [[Julie Woodcock]] and [[Brian Stelfreeze]]'s ''CyCops'', none of their comics publications sold as well as ''Southern Knights'', and by the end of that year they had stopped publishing any other titles. In mid-1989 ''Southern Knights'' was canceled as well, and the Comics Interview imprint was again devoted solely to magazines and trade publications although they would co-publish ''Southern Knights'' No. 35 and 36 in 1992.\n\n; Comics Interview\nIn 1983, Kraft founded ''David Anthony Kraft's Comics Interview'', with ran for 150 issues<ref>{{cite journal|title= Newswatch: ''Comics Interview'' Gives Up the Ghost|journal= [[The Comics Journal]]|issue= 183|page= 28|publisher= [[Fantagraphics Books]]|date= January 1996|location= Seattle, Washington}}</ref> between 1983 and 1995,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://comics.lib.msu.edu/rri/krri/kra.htm#kraftda |title=Index to the Comic Art Collection |publisher=[[Michigan State University Libraries]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5sbXKC3fK?url=http://comics.lib.msu.edu/rri/krri/kra.htm |archivedate=September 9, 2010 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and garnered [[Eisner Award|Eisner]] and [[Eagle Award (comics)|Eagle Award]] nominations. As suggested by the title, each issue of ''Comics Interview'' was filled entirely with in-depth creator interviews.\n\n=== Literary agent ===\nSince 1974, Kraft has been the [[literary agent]] for the estate of pulp author [[Otis Adelbert Kline]].\n\n==Influences and personal life==\nKraft counts science fiction author [[Leigh Brackett]], [[Stan Lee]], and writer [[E. Hoffmann Price]] as mentors.<ref name=\"DragonCon\" /> He currently lives in [[Clayton, Georgia]].{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n===Books===\n* ''Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band'' (Junior Press, 1979)\n* ''The Compleat OAK Leaves: Volume One of the Official Journal of Otis Adelbert Kline and his Works'' (editor) (Fictioneer Press, 1980)\n* ''Stan Lee Presents the Incredible Hulk'' pop-up book (Marvel Comics Group, 1980)\n* ''Captain America: The Secret Story of Marvel's Star-Spangled Super Hero'' (Children's Press, 1981)\n* ''The Fantastic Four: The Secret Story of Marvel's Cosmic Quartet'' (Children's Press, 1981)\n* ''The Incredible Hulk: The Secret Story of Marvel's Gamma-powered Goliath'' (Children's Press, 1981)\n* ''Attack of the Tarantula'' (Intervisual Communications, 1982)\n* ''The Dark Crystal'' (Marvel Books, 1982)\n* ''Stan Lee Presents the Incredible Hulk Pop-up Book, \"Trapped\"'' (Marvel Comics Group, 1982)\n* ''Fantastic Four vs. the Frightful Four'' coloring book (Marvel Books, 1983)\n* ''Heathcliff, #1 Cat at the Show''  coloring and activity book (Marvel Books, 1983)\n* ''Heathcliff at The Circus'' coloring book (Marvel Books, 1983)\n* ''The Treasure of Time'' (Marvel Books, 1983)\n* ''The Amazing Spider-Man: The Big Top Mystery'' (Marvel Books, 1984)\n* ''The Amazing Spider-Man and Wolverine in The Crime of the Centuries'' (Marvel Books, 1984)\n* ''Ghost Knights of Camelot'' (Avon Books, 1984) {{ISBN|978-0-380-89276-1}}\n* ''[[Micro Adventure]] no. 6: Robot Race'' (Scholastic, 1984) {{ISBN|0-590-33170-1}}\n* ''Marvel Super Heroes Secret Wars: Captain America and Iron Man in Escape from Doom'' (Budget Books, 1986)\n* ''Marvel Super Heroes Jumbo Coloring & Activity Book'' (Marvel Books, 1987)\n\n===Comic books===\n\n====Atlas/Seaboard Comics====\n* ''[[Demon Hunter (comics)|Demon Hunter]]'' #1 (1975)\n\n====DC Comics====\n* ''[[Blackhawk (DC Comics)|Blackhawk]]'' #247\u2013248 (1976)\n* ''[[Kamandi]], The Last Boy on Earth'' #44\u201346 (1976)\n* ''[[Richard Dragon]], Kung-Fu Fighter'' #11\u201312 (1976)\n* ''[[Secret Society of Super Villains]]'' #2\u20134 (1976)\n* ''[[Swamp Thing (comic book)|Swamp Thing]]'' #24 (1976)\n* ''[[Tarzan in comics|Tarzan]]'' #254 (1976)\n* ''[[World's Finest Comics]]'' #293, 295\u2013300, 302\u2013307 (1983\u20131984)\n\n====Marvel Comics====\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}} \n* ''[[Captain America (comic book)|Captain America]]'' #265\u2013266, 271, 273\u2013274 (1982)\n* ''[[Tower of Shadows|Creatures on the Loose]]'' #33\u201337 ([[John Jameson (comics)|Man-Wolf]]) (1975)\n* ''[[Defenders (comics)|Defenders]]'' #44\u201356, 58\u201368, 89 (1977\u20131980)\n* ''[[The Tomb of Dracula|Giant-Size Dracula]]'' #4\u20135 (1975)\n* ''Haunt of Horror'' #5 (1975)\n* ''[[The Rampaging Hulk|The Hulk]]'' #24 (1980)\n* ''[[Logan's Run (film)#Legacy|Logan's Run]]'' #2\u20135 (1977)\n* ''[[Marvel Comics Super Special]]'' #4 (''[[The Beatles|The Beatles Story]]'') (1978)\n* ''[[Marvel Fanfare]]'' #4, 17 (1982\u20131984)\n* ''[[Marvel Premiere]]'' #45\u201346 (1978\u20131979)\n* ''[[Marvel Preview]]'' #12\u201314 (1977\u20131978)\n* ''[[Marvel Spotlight]]'' #33 (1977)\n* ''Marvel Super Special'' #7 (''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band (film)|Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]''); #24 (''[[The Dark Crystal]]'') (1979\u20131983)\n* ''[[Marvel Super-Heroes (comics)|Marvel Super-Heroes]]'' vol. 2 #15 (1993)\n* ''[[Marvel Team-Up]]'' #109 (1981)\n* ''[[Marvel Two-in-One]]'' #41, 88\u201389, 94\u201395 (1978\u20131983)\n* ''[[Savage She-Hulk]]'' #2\u201325 (1980\u20131982)\n* ''[[The Spectacular Spider-Man]] Annual'' #3 (1981)\n* ''[[Tales of the Zombie]]'' #8 (1974)\n* ''[[Tarzan in comics|Tarzan]]'' #12, 15\u201321 (1978\u20131979)\n* ''[[Thor (Marvel Comics)|Thor]]'' #253 ([[Asgard (comics)|Tales of Asgard]] backup story) (1976)\n* ''[[What If (comics)|What If...?]]'' #37 (1983)\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{comicbookdb|type=creator|id=697|title=David Anthony Kraft}}\n* [http://www.mikesamazingworld.com/mikes/features/creator.php?creatorid=578 David Anthony Kraft] at Mike's Amazing World of Comics\n* [http://www.maelmill-insi.de/UHBMCC/namk17.htm#N354 David Anthony Kraft] at the Unofficial Handbook of Marvel Comics Creators\n* [http://joeguide.com/interviews/dak/entirelist.shtml Alphabetical index of the first 100 issues of ''Comics Interview''.]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[Defenders (comics)|The Defenders]]'' writer| before=[[Gerry Conway]]| after=[[Ed Hannigan]]| years=1977\u20131979}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[She-Hulk|Savage She-Hulk]]'' writer| before=[[Stan Lee]]| after= n/a| years=1980\u20131982}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[World's Finest Comics]]'' writer| before=[[Doug Moench]]| after=[[Kurt Busiek]]| years=1983\u20131984}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kraft, David Anthony}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:American comics writers]]\n[[Category:American magazine editors]]\n[[Category:American magazine publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:Comics critics]]\n[[Category:Literary agents]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics writers]]\n[[Category:People from Clayton, Georgia]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1005:b005:25e1:ec5c:30b6:81af:5d20", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Anthony_Kraft"}
{"title_page": "Paul J. Smith (arts administrator)", "text_new": "'''Paul J. Smith''' (8 September 1931 \u2013 27 April 2020) was an arts administrator, [[curator]], and artist based in [[New York City|New York]]. Director Emeritus of the [[Museum of Arts & Design|Museum of Arts and Design]] (formerly the Museum of Contemporary Crafts, of which he served as director in 1963\u20131979, and, following the change of the museum's name to American Craft Museum, 1979\u20131987<ref>\"Museum History,\" Museum of Arts & Design, http://madmuseum.org/about/history. Accessed September 14, 2013.</ref>), Smith was professionally involved with the art, craft, and design fields since the early 1950s and was closely associated with the twentieth-century \"[[studio craft]] movement\" [[American craft|in the United States]]. He joined the staff of the American Craftsmen's Council (ACC, now the [[American Craft Council]]) in 1957, and was appointed Director of the Museum of Contemporary Crafts in 1963.<ref>\u201cAbout the Council: Our History,\u201d American Craft Council, http://craftcouncil.org/history. Accessed August 15, 2013.</ref> In September 1987, after 30 years with ACC, he assumed the position of Director Emeritus to provide independent consulting for museums, arts organizations, and collectors.<ref>\"[http://craftcouncil.org/post/month-american-craft-council-history-september-2012 This Month in Craft History: September 2012]\", American Craft Council. Accessed 15 August 2013.</ref>\n\nSmith died at home in New York City on 27 April 2020, age 88.<ref>\"Paul J. Smith (1931-2020),\" Disegno Daily, https://www.disegnodaily.com/newsfeed/paul-j-smith-1931-2020, accessed 29 April 2020.</ref>\n\n== Early years and education ==\n\nRaised in [[Bennington, New York]], Smith graduated from [[Attica (town), New York|Attica]] High School in 1948 and attended the [[Art Institute of Buffalo]], where he received a scholarship and studied with local artists who served as faculty members, including [[Charles Burchfield]] and James Vullo. With an interest in exploring craft skills, he took courses at the local Buffalo [[YWCA]] craft program, where he later taught [[studio pottery|ceramic]] classes. He also took a few classes at the School for American Craftsmen (now the [[School for American Crafts]]) at the [[Rochester Institute of Technology]]; this interest led   to his membership in the organization Buffalo Craftsmen, where he served as president in 1962, and his active involvement with York State Craftsmen, a state organization that held an annual craft fair in [[Ithaca, New York]].\n\nHe took a position in the display department of the [[Flint & Kent]] department store in 1953, and was appointed Display Director there in 1955.<ref>A brief overview of Smith's early career can be found in Glenn Adamson, \u201cGatherings: Creating the Studio Craft Movement,\u201d in Jeannine Falino, ed., Crafting Modernism: Midcentury American Art and Design (New York: Abrams; Museum of Arts and Design, 2011), p. 41, as well as a biographical entry in the same text, p. 311\u201312. Fuller documentation exists at the ACC Library archives and in the Paul J. Smith Papers, 1955\u20132011 at the Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution; see http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/paul-j-smith-papers-11572.</ref>\n\n== Artistic activity ==\n\nDuring the 1950s, Smith's paintings and other artworks (signed Paul John Smith) were included in several regional exhibitions, including the Western New York Show at the [[Albright Knox Art Gallery|Albright Art Gallery]] in Buffalo, and the Finger Lakes Show at the [[Memorial Art Gallery]] in Rochester. In 1957 he was included in the new talent listing of the magazine ''[[Art in America]]''. His jewelry and wood forms were shown in national competitions such as \"Fiber, Clay and Metal\" (1955\u201357) at the [[Saint Paul Gallery and School of Art]] and the ACC \"Young Americans\" competitions (1954, 1956, and 1958). In 1956, his work in wood was awarded a Young Americans Certificate of Merit. He also was represented in ''Craftsmanship in a Changing World'' (1956), the inaugural exhibition at the Museum of Contemporary Crafts.<ref>See ''Craftsmanship in a Changing World'' (New York: American Craftsmen's Council, 1956). Accessible online at http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll5/id/2614. Accessed 14 September 2013.</ref>\n\nFrom the 1980s, Smith focused on photography, extensively documenting public events in New York and internationally, including the annual West Indian Parade and [[Coney Island Mermaid Parade]]. His photo collection also included images of more than 300 artists, collectors, and other individuals involved with the American studio craft movement from 1985 into the first decades of the twenty-first century. In 2015\u201316, exhibitions of his photographic portraits were mounted at the [[Fuller Craft Museum]] and the [[Arizona State University Art Museum]].<ref>\"Paul J. Smith Portraits: A Photographic Journal of the Studio Craft Community,\" Fuller Craft Museum, https://fullercraft.org/event/paul-j-smith-portraits-photographic-journal-studio-craft-community/, accessed 29 April 2020; and \"Paul J. Smith Portraits: A Photographic Journal of the Ceramic Community,\" ASU Art Museum, https://asuevents.asu.edu/content/paul-j-smith-portraits-photographic-journal-ceramic-community, accessed 29 April 2020.</ref>\n\n== Curatorial career ==\n\nUpon joining the staff of the American Craftsmen's Council in 1957, Smith established a new ACC program for [[Travelling exhibition|traveling educational exhibitions]]. Since 1960, when he became officially involved with the museum, he has been responsible for organizing and presenting over 200 exhibitions, ranging from surveys of contemporary craft to one-artist retrospectives and innovative thematic exhibitions.<ref>For a list of Museum of Contemporary Crafts and American Craft Museum exhibitions from 1956\u201390, which includes images of the works included in certain exhibitions and several digitized catalogues, see \"Museum of Contemporary Crafts/American Craft Museum Finding Aid (1956-1990),\" American Craft Council, https://craftcouncil.org/library/archives. Accessed 14 September 2013. The exhibitions and other projects Smith organized received extensive press coverage in national publications; selected press material is held in the ACC Library archives.</ref> Notable theme-focused exhibitions he organized include ''[http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll6/id/1276/rec/1 Cookies and Breads: The Baker's Art]'' (1966), ''[http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll6/id/2647/rec/2 Designed for Production: The Craftsmen's Approach]'' (1964), ''The Teapot'' (1965), ''The Door'' (1968), ''[http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll6/id/1237/rec/1 Body Covering]'' (1968), ''[http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll6/id/2718/rec/3 Plastic as Plastic]'' (1969), ''[http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll7/id/2812/rec/5 Objects for Preparing Food]'' (1973), ''[http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll7/id/2863/rec/40 Portable World]'' (1974), and ''[http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll7/id/2034/rec/1 The Great American Foot]'' (1978). He initiated more than 75 one-artist exhibitions, including retrospectives for [[Dorothy Liebes]] (1970) and [[Peter Voulkos]] (1978).<ref>Images from these retrospectives are available online through the ACC Library's Artist Archive Collection: [http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/search/collection/p15785coll13!p15785coll6!p15785coll7!p15785coll1/searchterm/dorothy%20liebes%20retrospective/field/all/mode/exact/conn/and/order/nosort/page/1 Dorothy Liebes] and [http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/search/collection/p15785coll13!p15785coll7!p15785coll8!p15785coll1/searchterm/Peter%20Voulkos:%20a%20retrospective/field/all/mode/exact/conn/and/order/nosort/page/1 Peter Voulkos]. Accessed 14 September 2013.</ref>\nSmith also played a pivotal role in opening the American Craft Museum's new facility at 40 W. 53rd Street in the fall of 1986. On that occasion, he curated the exhibition ''[http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll8/id/3032/rec/1 Craft Today: Poetry of the Physical]'', which toured nationally after its New York premier. A revised version, ''Craft Today USA'', toured to fifteen European cities under the auspices of the [[United States Information Agency]]'s (USIA) Arts America Program from 1989 to 1993.<ref>''Craft Today USA: Final Report ''(New York: American Craft Museum; United States Information Agency, 1993). See also, e.g., Betty Werther, \"Craft Today USA,\" in ''American Craft ''49, no. 5 (October/November 1989), pp. 32\u201339. Documentation on the tour of the exhibition and its press reception in the cities to which it traveled is held in the ACC Library archives.</ref>\n\nIn addition to organizing exhibitions at the museum in New York, he served as a curatorial adviser for a number of other important exhibitions of contemporary craft, including ''Objects USA'' (1969), a survey collection of craft works assembled by gallery owner Lee Nordness that toured in both the United States and Europe;<ref>Exhibition catalogue: Lee Nordness, ''Objects U.S.A.'' (New York: Viking, 1970), p. 21. See also \"Lee Nordness Business Records and Papers circa 1931\u20131992,\" Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution ([http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/lee-nordness-business-records-and-papers-7232 Collection Summary]), or Glenn Adamson, \u201cGatherings: Creating the Studio Craft Movement,\u201d in Jeannine Falino, ed., ''Crafting Modernism: Midcentury American Art and Design'' (New York: Abrams; Museum of Arts and Design, 2011), p. 43.</ref> ''Craft, Art & Religion'' (1978), the first contemporary craft exhibition to be held at the [[Vatican Museums|Vatican]]; and ''In Praise of Hands'' (1978), the first international craft exhibition in [[Toronto]].<ref>Sandra Alfoldy, ''Crafting Identity: The Development of Professional Fine Craft in Canada'' (Montreal: McGill-Queen's University Press, 2005), p. 210.</ref> He also served on the juries of ''Things People Make'' (1981) at the Durban Art Gallery in [[Durban]], South Africa; ''World Glass Now'' (1982) in [[Sapporo|Sapporo, Japan]]; and numerous other international competitions. In 2001, as project director and guest curator for the American Craft Museum, he organized the major exhibition ''Objects for Use: Handmade by Design''.<ref>See ''Objects for Use: Handmade by Design'' (New York: H.N. Abrams; American Craft Museum, 2001).</ref>\n\nIn early 2020, the Design Museum at the [[University of California, Davis]] hosted an exhibition of African, Asian, and South American textiles from Smith's personal collection alongside contemporary work by UC Davis design students.<ref>\"Appreciation and Adaptation: Homage to Global Textiles,\" UC David Design Museum, https://arts.ucdavis.edu/exhibition/closed-appreciation-and-adaptation-homage-global-textiles. Accessed 29 April 2020.</ref>\n\n== Other professional activity ==\n\nFrom the 1960s, Smith served on numerous boards and committees for arts organizations, including [[Haystack Mountain School of Crafts]], [[Penland School of Crafts]], World Craft Foundation, [[Atlantic Center for the Arts]], [[Boston University]] Program in Artisantry, [[Parsons The New School for Design]], the [[Pilchuck Glass School]], Friends of American Art in Religion, and Friends of [[Fiber art|Fiber Art]]. He was a trustee of the [[Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation]]<ref>\"Board of Trustees,\" Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation, http://louiscomforttiffanyfoundation.org/board_of_trustees.html. Accessed 15 September 2013.</ref> and president of the [[Lenore Tawney|Lenore G. Tawney]] Foundation.\n\nSmith traveled to 46 countries to lecture, serve on competition juries, participate in conferences, consult with arts organizations, and conduct research for exhibitions. He helped with the planning of the First Congress of Craftsmen in New York (1964), when the [[World Crafts Council]] (WCC) was formed, and attended all subsequent WCC conferences. He was also an invited guest for cultural exchange by the governments of India, Germany, Morocco, Australia, Sweden and Finland. Through the USIA, he gave lectures and workshops in Papua New Guinea, Rwanda, and Botswana as well as in Australia and many European cities. As a member of the professional advisory committee for the \u201cGift to the Nation\u201d Millennium Project by the Friends of Art and Preservation in Embassies, he assisted in assembling a collection of craft works for permanent placement in [[United States embassies]].<ref>Friends of Art and Preservation in Embassies published a volume documenting the project: see Emily Russell, ed., ''Gift to the Nation ''(Washington D.C.: Friends of Art and Preservation in Embassies, 2001).</ref> Smith also advised The Center for U.S-China Arts Exchange at [[Columbia University]] from 1995 on their project dealing with ethnic culture in the [[Yunnan Province]], and made three trips to China in 1995, 1997, and 2000.\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n\nIn May 1987, the Parsons School of Design of the New School for Social Research (now [[Parsons The New School for Design]]) awarded Smith an Honorary [[Doctor of Fine Arts|Doctorate of Fine Arts]] for his contributions to craft and design education. He is an Honorary Fellow of the American Craft Council,<ref>\"American Craft Council College of Fellows,\" American Craft Council, https://craftcouncil.org/about-acc/acc-awards/american-craft-council-college-of-fellows. Accessed 15 September.</ref> and an Honorary International Member of the Canadian Craft Council (now the [[Canadian Crafts Federation]]). The ACC awarded him the 2009 [[Aileen Osborn Webb]] Award for Philanthropy in recognition of exceptional curatorial contributions to the craft field.<ref>\"Aileen Osborn Webb Awards 2009,\" American Craft Council, November 9, 2009, http://craftcouncil.org/magazine/article/aileen-osborn-webb-awards-2009. Accessed 14 September 2013.</ref> In November 2011, he received a \u201cLegends\u201d Award from the Watershed Center for the Ceramic Arts. Smith was also awarded the Albert Nelson Marquis Lifetime Achievement Award by [[Marquis Who's Who]] in 2019.<ref>\"Paul J. Smith Presented with the Albert Nelson Marquis Lifetime Achievement Award by Marquis Who's Who,\" Marquis Who's Who, September 23, 2019, https://www.24-7pressrelease.com/press-release/466255/paul-j-smith-presented-with-the-albert-nelson-marquis-lifetime-achievement-award-by-marquis-whos-who. Accessed 27 October 2019.</ref>\n\n== Selected publications ==\n\n=== Books and exhibition catalogues ===\n\n''Craft Today: Poetry of the Physical'' (New York: Weidenfeld & Nicolson; American Craft Museum, 1986).\n\n''Objects for Use: Handmade by Design'' (New York: H.N. Abrams; American Craft Museum, 2001).\n\n''Masters of Craft: 224 Artists in Fiber, Clay, Glass, Metal and Wood'' (Pennsylvania: Schiffer Publishing; 2015).\n\n<small>Note: Smith produced and edited numerous other exhibition catalogues during his tenure at the Museum of Contemporary Crafts/American Craft Museum, many of which are accessible online at the [http://craftcouncil.org/library American Craft Council Library].</small>\n\n=== Essays and articles ===\n\n\"Standards for Collecting Craft Art,\" in ''Craft Art and Religion: Proceedings of the Second International Seminar, 1978'' (New York: The Committee of Religion and Art of America, 1979), pp.&nbsp;49\u201352.\n\n\"Jurors' Statement,\" in Hokkaid\u014dritsu Kindai Bijutsukan, et al., ''World Glass Now '82'' (Sapporo: Hokkaido Museum of Modern Art, 1982).\n\n\"A Tribute to Lenore,\" in Kathleen Nugent Mangan, ed., ''Lenore Tawney: A Retrospective'' (New York: American Craft Museum and Rizzoli, 1990), p.&nbsp;13.\n\n\"Foreword,\" in Barbara Lovenheim, ed., ''Breaking Ground: A Century of Craft Art in Western New York'' (Rochester, N.Y.: Memorial Art Gallery of the University of Rochester, 2010), p.&nbsp;7.\n\n\"Toshiko Takaezu: Six Decades,\" in Peter Held, et al., ''The Art of Toshiko Takaezu: In the Language of Silence'' (Chapel Hill, NC: University of North Carolina Press, 2011), pp.&nbsp;13\u201317.\n\nContributed to Caroline M. Hannah, \"An 'Exploding Craft Market,' 1945\u20131969,\" in Jeannine Falino, ed., ''Crafting Modernism: Midcentury American Art and Design ''(New York: Abrams; Museum of Arts and Design, 2011), pp.&nbsp;141\u2013143.\n\n\"Formative Years: From Korea to America,\" in Jane Milosch, ed., ''Chunghi Choo and Her Students: Contemporary Art and New Forms in Metal'' (Stuttgart: Arnoldsche Art Publishers, 2020).\n\n=== Oral history interviews ===\n\nOral history interview with Paul J. Smith, conducted by Richard Polsky, 1990. Columbia Center for Oral History, Columbia University Libraries. [http://oralhistoryportal.cul.columbia.edu/document.php?id=ldpd_7923237 Catalogue record]\n\nOral history interview with Paul J. Smith, conducted by Lloyd E. Herman, April 19\u201320, 2010. Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution. [http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-paul-j-smith-15795 Transcript]\n\nOral history interview with Paul J. Smith, conducted by Colin E. Fanning, April 24, 2013. Bard Graduate Center Craft, Art and Design Oral History Project, [[Bard Graduate Center]]. [http://bgccraftartdesign.org/items/show/9 Transcript]\n\n=== Oral history interviews conducted by Smith ===\n\n[[Ed Rossbach]], August 27\u201329, 2002. Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution. [http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/oral-history-interviews-ed-rossbach-and-katherine-westphal-6147 Collection record]\n\n[[Katherine Westphal]], September 3\u20137, 2002. Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution. [http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/oral-history-interviews-ed-rossbach-and-katherine-westphal-6147 Collection record]\n\nSusan Peterson, March 1, 2004. Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution. [http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-susan-peterson-12242 Transcript]\n\nAlice Parrot, July 10, 2005. Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution. [http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-alice-kagawa-parrott-13248 Transcript]\n\n[[John Mason (artist)|John Mason]], August 28, 2006. Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution. [http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-john-mason-13582 Transcript]\n\n[[Mark Lindquist]], August 12, 2009. Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution. [http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-mark-lindquist-15710 Collection record]\n \nLloyd Herman, September 21, 2010. Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution. [http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-lloyd-e-herman-16029 Collection record]\n\n=== Published features or interviews ===\n\n''ACC Outlook '', [http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll1/id/198/rec/2 Vol. 4, No. 5] (October 1963), pp.&nbsp;1\u20132.\n\n\"An Interview with Paul J. Smith,\" in ''Museum News ''50, no. 6 (February 1972), pp.&nbsp;15\u201319.\n\nRobert Kehlmann, \"Consummate Connoisseur,\" in ''American Craft'' 47, no. 5 (October/November 1987), pp.&nbsp;50\u201355.\n\n\"Remembering the American Craft Museum,\" in ''Studio Potter'' 32, no. 1 (December 2003), pp.&nbsp;3\u201316.\n\nSuzanne Ramljak, \"Interview: Paul J. Smith,\" in ''Metalsmith ''27, no. 5 (2007), pp.&nbsp;20\u201323.\n\nJoyce Lovelace, \"Who Was Aileen Osborn Webb?\" in ''American Craft'' 71, no. 4 (August/September 2011), pp.&nbsp;47\u201349.\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Archival sources ==\n\nThe [http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/paul-j-smith-papers-11572 Paul J. Smith Papers, 1955\u20132011], Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution, Washington, D.C.\n\nThe [http://craftcouncil.org/library/archives American Craft Council Library and Archives], American Craft Council, Minneapolis, Minnesota.\n\n== External links ==\n\n*The [http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/projects/laitman Nanette L. Laitman Documentation Project for Craft and Decorative Arts In America], Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution.\n*''[http://collections.madmuseum.org/code/emuseum.asp?style=browse&currentrecord=57&page=seealso&profile=exhibitions&searchdesc=Past%20Exhibitions&searchstring=Past/,/greater%20than/,/0/,/false/,/true&action=searchrequest&style=single&currentrecord=57 Objects USA] ''exhibition in the Museum of Arts and Design collections database.\n*\"[http://www.craftinamerica.org/episodes/process/ Episode V: Process],\" ''Craft in America'', PBS, 2009. Interview segment with Paul J. Smith: {{YouTube|32Eo7K5JHhY}}\n*[http://www.schifferbooks.com/masters-of-craft-224-artists-in-fiber-clay-glass-metal-and-wood-portraits-by-paul-j-smith-5805.html ''Masters of Craft: 224 Artists in Fiber, Clay, Glass, Metal and Wood''], Schiffer Publishing, 2015.\n\n{{American Craft Council}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Paul J.}}\n[[Category:American curators]]\n[[Category:Art curators]]\n[[Category:Directors of museums in the United States]]\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Wyoming County, New York]]\n", "text_old": "'''Paul J. Smith''' (8 September 1931 \u2013 27 April 2020) was an arts administrator, [[curator]], and artist based in [[New York City|New York]]. Director Emeritus of the [[Museum of Arts & Design|Museum of Arts and Design]] (formerly the Museum of Contemporary Crafts, of which he served as director in 1963\u20131979, and, following the change of the museum's name to American Craft Museum, 1979\u20131987<ref>\"Museum History,\" Museum of Arts & Design, http://madmuseum.org/about/history. Accessed September 14, 2013.</ref>), Smith was professionally involved with the art, craft, and design fields since the early 1950s and was closely associated with the twentieth-century \"[[studio craft]] movement\" [[American craft|in the United States]]. He joined the staff of the American Craftsmen's Council (ACC, now the [[American Craft Council]]) in 1957, and was appointed Director of the Museum of Contemporary Crafts in 1963.<ref>\u201cAbout the Council: Our History,\u201d American Craft Council, http://craftcouncil.org/history. Accessed August 15, 2013.</ref> In September 1987, after 30 years with ACC, he assumed the position of Director Emeritus to provide independent consulting for museums, arts organizations, and collectors.<ref>\"[http://craftcouncil.org/post/month-american-craft-council-history-september-2012 This Month in Craft History: September 2012]\", American Craft Council. Accessed 15 August 2013.</ref>\n\nSmith died at home in New York City on 27 April 2020, age 88.<ref>\"Paul J. Smith (1931-2020),\" Disegno Daily, https://www.disegnodaily.com/newsfeed/paul-j-smith-1931-2020, accessed 29 April 2020.</ref>\n\n== Early years and education ==\n\nRaised in [[Bennington, New York]], Smith graduated from [[Attica (town), New York|Attica]] High School in 1948 and attended the [[Art Institute of Buffalo]], where he received a scholarship and studied with local artists who served as faculty members, including [[Charles Burchfield]] and James Vullo. With an interest in exploring craft skills, he took courses at the local Buffalo [[YWCA]] craft program, where he later taught [[studio pottery|ceramic]] classes. He also took a few classes at the School for American Craftsmen (now the [[School for American Crafts]]) at the [[Rochester Institute of Technology]]; this interest led   to his membership in the organization Buffalo Craftsmen, where he served as president in 1962, and his active involvement with York State Craftsmen, a state organization that held an annual craft fair in [[Ithaca, New York]].\n\nHe took a position in the display department of the [[Flint & Kent]] department store in 1953, and was appointed Display Director there in 1955.<ref>A brief overview of Smith's early career can be found in Glenn Adamson, \u201cGatherings: Creating the Studio Craft Movement,\u201d in Jeannine Falino, ed., Crafting Modernism: Midcentury American Art and Design (New York: Abrams; Museum of Arts and Design, 2011), p. 41, as well as a biographical entry in the same text, p. 311\u201312. Fuller documentation exists at the ACC Library archives and in the Paul J. Smith Papers, 1955\u20132011 at the Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution; see http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/paul-j-smith-papers-11572.</ref>\n\n== Artistic activity ==\n\nDuring the 1950s, Smith's paintings and other artworks (signed Paul John Smith) were included in several regional exhibitions, including the Western New York Show at the [[Albright Knox Art Gallery|Albright Art Gallery]] in Buffalo, and the Finger Lakes Show at the [[Memorial Art Gallery]] in Rochester. In 1957 he was included in the new talent listing of the magazine ''[[Art in America]]''. His jewelry and wood forms were shown in national competitions such as \"Fiber, Clay and Metal\" (1955\u201357) at the [[Saint Paul Gallery and School of Art]] and the ACC \"Young Americans\" competitions (1954, 1956, and 1958). In 1956, his work in wood was awarded a Young Americans Certificate of Merit. He also was represented in ''Craftsmanship in a Changing World'' (1956), the inaugural exhibition at the Museum of Contemporary Crafts.<ref>See ''Craftsmanship in a Changing World'' (New York: American Craftsmen's Council, 1956). Accessible online at http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll5/id/2614. Accessed 14 September 2013.</ref>\n\nFrom the 1980s, Smith focused on photography, extensively documenting public events in New York and internationally, including the annual West Indian Parade and [[Coney Island Mermaid Parade]]. His photo collection also included images of more than 300 artists, collectors, and other individuals involved with the American studio craft movement from 1985 into the first decades of the twenty-first century. In 2015-16, exhibitions of his photographic portraits were mounted at the [[Fuller Craft Museum]] and the [[Arizona State University Art Museum]].<ref>\"Paul J. Smith Portraits: A Photographic Journal of the Studio Craft Community,\" Fuller Craft Museum, https://fullercraft.org/event/paul-j-smith-portraits-photographic-journal-studio-craft-community/, accessed 29 April 2020; and \"Paul J. Smith Portraits: A Photographic Journal of the Ceramic Community,\" ASU Art Museum, https://asuevents.asu.edu/content/paul-j-smith-portraits-photographic-journal-ceramic-community, accessed 29 April 2020.</ref>\n\n== Curatorial career ==\n\nUpon joining the staff of the American Craftsmen's Council in 1957, Smith established a new ACC program for [[Travelling exhibition|traveling educational exhibitions]]. Since 1960, when he became officially involved with the museum, he has been responsible for organizing and presenting over 200 exhibitions, ranging from surveys of contemporary craft to one-artist retrospectives and innovative thematic exhibitions.<ref>For a list of Museum of Contemporary Crafts and American Craft Museum exhibitions from 1956\u201390, which includes images of the works included in certain exhibitions and several digitized catalogues, see \"Museum of Contemporary Crafts/American Craft Museum Finding Aid (1956-1990),\" American Craft Council, https://craftcouncil.org/library/archives. Accessed 14 September 2013. The exhibitions and other projects Smith organized received extensive press coverage in national publications; selected press material is held in the ACC Library archives.</ref> Notable theme-focused exhibitions he organized include ''[http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll6/id/1276/rec/1 Cookies and Breads: The Baker's Art]'' (1966), ''[http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll6/id/2647/rec/2 Designed for Production: The Craftsmen's Approach]'' (1964), ''The Teapot'' (1965), ''The Door'' (1968), ''[http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll6/id/1237/rec/1 Body Covering]'' (1968), ''[http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll6/id/2718/rec/3 Plastic as Plastic]'' (1969), ''[http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll7/id/2812/rec/5 Objects for Preparing Food]'' (1973), ''[http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll7/id/2863/rec/40 Portable World]'' (1974), and ''[http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll7/id/2034/rec/1 The Great American Foot]'' (1978). He initiated more than 75 one-artist exhibitions, including retrospectives for [[Dorothy Liebes]] (1970) and [[Peter Voulkos]] (1978).<ref>Images from these retrospectives are available online through the ACC Library's Artist Archive Collection: [http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/search/collection/p15785coll13!p15785coll6!p15785coll7!p15785coll1/searchterm/dorothy%20liebes%20retrospective/field/all/mode/exact/conn/and/order/nosort/page/1 Dorothy Liebes] and [http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/search/collection/p15785coll13!p15785coll7!p15785coll8!p15785coll1/searchterm/Peter%20Voulkos:%20a%20retrospective/field/all/mode/exact/conn/and/order/nosort/page/1 Peter Voulkos]. Accessed 14 September 2013.</ref>\nSmith also played a pivotal role in opening the American Craft Museum's new facility at 40 W. 53rd Street in the fall of 1986. On that occasion, he curated the exhibition ''[http://digital.craftcouncil.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15785coll8/id/3032/rec/1 Craft Today: Poetry of the Physical]'', which toured nationally after its New York premier. A revised version, ''Craft Today USA'', toured to fifteen European cities under the auspices of the [[United States Information Agency]]'s (USIA) Arts America Program from 1989 to 1993.<ref>''Craft Today USA: Final Report ''(New York: American Craft Museum; United States Information Agency, 1993). See also, e.g., Betty Werther, \"Craft Today USA,\" in ''American Craft ''49, no. 5 (October/November 1989), pp. 32\u201339. Documentation on the tour of the exhibition and its press reception in the cities to which it traveled is held in the ACC Library archives.</ref>\n\nIn addition to organizing exhibitions at the museum in New York, he served as a curatorial adviser for a number of other important exhibitions of contemporary craft, including ''Objects USA'' (1969), a survey collection of craft works assembled by gallery owner Lee Nordness that toured in both the United States and Europe;<ref>Exhibition catalogue: Lee Nordness, ''Objects U.S.A.'' (New York: Viking, 1970), p. 21. See also \"Lee Nordness Business Records and Papers circa 1931\u20131992,\" Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution ([http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/lee-nordness-business-records-and-papers-7232 Collection Summary]), or Glenn Adamson, \u201cGatherings: Creating the Studio Craft Movement,\u201d in Jeannine Falino, ed., ''Crafting Modernism: Midcentury American Art and Design'' (New York: Abrams; Museum of Arts and Design, 2011), p. 43.</ref> ''Craft, Art & Religion'' (1978), the first contemporary craft exhibition to be held at the [[Vatican Museums|Vatican]]; and ''In Praise of Hands'' (1978), the first international craft exhibition in [[Toronto]].<ref>Sandra Alfoldy, ''Crafting Identity: The Development of Professional Fine Craft in Canada'' (Montreal: McGill-Queen's University Press, 2005), p. 210.</ref> He also served on the juries of ''Things People Make'' (1981) at the Durban Art Gallery in [[Durban]], South Africa; ''World Glass Now'' (1982) in [[Sapporo|Sapporo, Japan]]; and numerous other international competitions. In 2001, as project director and guest curator for the American Craft Museum, he organized the major exhibition ''Objects for Use: Handmade by Design''.<ref>See ''Objects for Use: Handmade by Design'' (New York: H.N. Abrams; American Craft Museum, 2001).</ref>\n\nIn early 2020, the Design Museum at the [[University of California, Davis]] hosted an exhibition of African, Asian, and South American textiles from Smith's personal collection alongside contemporary work by UC Davis design students.<ref>\"Appreciation and Adaptation: Homage to Global Textiles,\" UC David Design Museum, https://arts.ucdavis.edu/exhibition/closed-appreciation-and-adaptation-homage-global-textiles. Accessed 29 April 2020.</ref>\n\n== Other professional activity ==\n\nFrom the 1960s, Smith served on numerous boards and committees for arts organizations, including [[Haystack Mountain School of Crafts]], [[Penland School of Crafts]], World Craft Foundation, [[Atlantic Center for the Arts]], [[Boston University]] Program in Artisantry, [[Parsons The New School for Design]], the [[Pilchuck Glass School]], Friends of American Art in Religion, and Friends of [[Fiber art|Fiber Art]]. He was a trustee of the [[Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation]]<ref>\"Board of Trustees,\" Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation, http://louiscomforttiffanyfoundation.org/board_of_trustees.html. Accessed 15 September 2013.</ref> and president of the [[Lenore Tawney|Lenore G. Tawney]] Foundation.\n\nSmith traveled to 46 countries to lecture, serve on competition juries, participate in conferences, consult with arts organizations, and conduct research for exhibitions. He helped with the planning of the First Congress of Craftsmen in New York (1964), when the [[World Crafts Council]] (WCC) was formed, and attended all subsequent WCC conferences. He was also an invited guest for cultural exchange by the governments of India, Germany, Morocco, Australia, Sweden and Finland. Through the USIA, he gave lectures and workshops in Papua New Guinea, Rwanda, and Botswana as well as in Australia and many European cities. As a member of the professional advisory committee for the \u201cGift to the Nation\u201d Millennium Project by the Friends of Art and Preservation in Embassies, he assisted in assembling a collection of craft works for permanent placement in [[United States embassies]].<ref>Friends of Art and Preservation in Embassies published a volume documenting the project: see Emily Russell, ed., ''Gift to the Nation ''(Washington D.C.: Friends of Art and Preservation in Embassies, 2001).</ref> Smith also advised The Center for U.S-China Arts Exchange at [[Columbia University]] from 1995 on their project dealing with ethnic culture in the [[Yunnan Province]], and made three trips to China in 1995, 1997, and 2000.\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n\nIn May 1987, the Parsons School of Design of the New School for Social Research (now [[Parsons The New School for Design]]) awarded Smith an Honorary [[Doctor of Fine Arts|Doctorate of Fine Arts]] for his contributions to craft and design education. He is an Honorary Fellow of the American Craft Council,<ref>\"American Craft Council College of Fellows,\" American Craft Council, https://craftcouncil.org/about-acc/acc-awards/american-craft-council-college-of-fellows. Accessed 15 September.</ref> and an Honorary International Member of the Canadian Craft Council (now the [[Canadian Crafts Federation]]). The ACC awarded him the 2009 [[Aileen Osborn Webb]] Award for Philanthropy in recognition of exceptional curatorial contributions to the craft field.<ref>\"Aileen Osborn Webb Awards 2009,\" American Craft Council, November 9, 2009, http://craftcouncil.org/magazine/article/aileen-osborn-webb-awards-2009. Accessed 14 September 2013.</ref> In November 2011, he received a \u201cLegends\u201d Award from the Watershed Center for the Ceramic Arts. Smith was also awarded the Albert Nelson Marquis Lifetime Achievement Award by [[Marquis Who's Who]] in 2019.<ref>\"Paul J. Smith Presented with the Albert Nelson Marquis Lifetime Achievement Award by Marquis Who's Who,\" Marquis Who's Who, September 23, 2019, https://www.24-7pressrelease.com/press-release/466255/paul-j-smith-presented-with-the-albert-nelson-marquis-lifetime-achievement-award-by-marquis-whos-who. Accessed 27 October 2019.</ref>\n\n== Selected publications ==\n\n=== Books and exhibition catalogues ===\n\n''Craft Today: Poetry of the Physical'' (New York: Weidenfeld & Nicolson; American Craft Museum, 1986).\n\n''Objects for Use: Handmade by Design'' (New York: H.N. Abrams; American Craft Museum, 2001).\n\n''Masters of Craft: 224 Artists in Fiber, Clay, Glass, Metal and Wood'' (Pennsylvania: Schiffer Publishing; 2015).\n\n<small>Note: Smith produced and edited numerous other exhibition catalogues during his tenure at the Museum of Contemporary Crafts/American Craft Museum, many of which are accessible online at the [http://craftcouncil.org/library American Craft Council Library].</small>\n\n=== Essays and articles ===\n\n\"Standards for Collecting Craft Art,\" in ''Craft Art and Religion: Proceedings of the Second International Seminar, 1978'' (New York: The Committee of Religion and Art of America, 1979), pp.&nbsp;49\u201352.\n\n\"Jurors' Statement,\" in Hokkaid\u014dritsu Kindai Bijutsukan, et al., ''World Glass Now '82'' (Sapporo: Hokkaido Museum of Modern Art, 1982).\n\n\"A Tribute to Lenore,\" in Kathleen Nugent Mangan, ed., ''Lenore Tawney: A Retrospective'' (New York: American Craft Museum and Rizzoli, 1990), p.&nbsp;13.\n\n\"Foreword,\" in Barbara Lovenheim, ed., ''Breaking Ground: A Century of Craft Art in Western New York'' (Rochester, N.Y.: Memorial Art Gallery of the University of Rochester, 2010), p.&nbsp;7.\n\n\"Toshiko Takaezu: Six Decades,\" in Peter Held, et al., ''The Art of Toshiko Takaezu: In the Language of Silence'' (Chapel Hill, NC: Uni