{"title_page": "Philippines Football League", "text_new": "{{short description|Top-level association football league in the Philippines}}\n{{Infobox football league\n|image = Philippines Football League Logo.png\n|image_size = 200px\n|country = Philippines\n|organiser = [[Liga Futbol Inc.]]\n|confed = [[Asian Football Confederation|AFC]] \n|founded = 2017\n|folded =\n|teams = 6\n|relegation =\n|level = 1\n|domest_cup = [[Copa Paulino Alcantara]]\n|confed_cup = [[AFC Champions League]] <br> [[AFC Cup]] \n|champions = [[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres\u2013Negros]] (3rd title)\n|season = [[2019 Philippines Football League|2019]]\n|most successful club = [[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres\u2013Negros]] (3 titles)\n|top_goalscorer = [[Bienvenido Mara\u00f1\u00f3n]] (67)<!--as of the end of the 2019 season -->\n|tv = \n|website = {{URL|www.pfl.org.ph}}\n|current = [[2020 Philippines Football League]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Philippines Football League''', commonly known as '''PFL''', is a Filipino professional [[association football]] league sanctioned by the [[Philippine Football Federation]] (PFF). It is the [[Philippines|Philippines']] highest level of men's club football, surpassing the [[United Football League (Philippines)|United Football League]] (UFL), which was previously the ''de facto'' top-tier league in the country.<ref name=\"ceres\">{{cite news|title=Ceres FC ready to apply for PFL license|url=http://visayandailystar.com/2016/October/15/sportnews1.htm|accessdate=16 October 2016|work=The Visayan Daily Star|date=15 October 2016}}</ref> Starting from the 2020 season, the league is also known as '''The Philippines Football League brought to you by Qatar Airways<ref>https://www.facebook.com/pg/PhilippinesFootballLeagueOfficial/about/</ref>''' due to the league's title sponsorship of [[Qatar Airways]]\n\nThe PFL followed a home-and-away format as opposed to the UFL, and has had three seasons thus far ([[2017 Philippines Football League|2017]], [[2018 Philippines Football League|2018]], [[2019 Philippines Football League|2019]]), which were all won by [[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres\u2013Negros]]. In 2018, financial and logistical issues forced the disestablishment of the PFL with the [[Philippine Premier League]] established in its place. However, with the folding of the PPL after just one match day, the PFL was revived in mid-May 2019.\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\nFollowing the success of the [[Philippines national football team|Philippines national team]] in the [[2010 AFF Championship|2010 AFF Suzuki Cup]], Philippine football experienced a renaissance. With no existing national football league, the [[Metro Manila]]-based [[United Football League (Philippines)|United Football League]] (UFL) became the ''de facto'' top-tier league in the Philippines. Under the guidance of the Football Alliance (FA) in partnership with United Football Clubs Association (UFCA), the UFL flourished. However, the PFF expressed the need to have a nationwide, community-based football league that is at par with the standards set by the [[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] (FIFA) and the [[Asian Football Confederation]] (AFC).<ref name=\"gma1\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/337938/sports/football/philippine-football-federation-set-to-launch-national-league |title=Philippine Football Federation set to launch national league |last=Bautista |first=Roehl Ni\u00f1o |date=2 December 2013 |work=[[GMA News]] |access-date=8 September 2016}}</ref> The UFL, which is under the [[National Capital Region F.A.|National Capital Region Football Association]], cannot be considered as a national league.\n\n===Foundations===\n[[File:PFL Philippines Nielsen Study Cited Localities map.svg|250px|thumb|alt=Map showing the 13 localities (provinces, cities or municipalities) in red deemed viable home venues for prospect clubs of the Philippines Football League|13 localities deemed viable home venues by the Nielsen Company for prospect clubs in the PFL.<ref name=\"cnnph1\"/>\n{{smalldiv|\n{{unbulleted list|'''[[Luzon]]''': [[Manila]], [[Makati]], [[Quezon City]], [[Marikina]], [[Bocaue, Bulacan|Bocaue]] ([[Bulacan]]), [[Laguna (province)|Laguna]], [[Pampanga]]|'''[[Visayas]]''': [[Cebu]], [[Bacolod]], [[Iloilo]]|'''[[Mindanao]]''': [[Davao City]], [[Cagayan de Oro]], [[Zamboanga City]]}}}}\n]]\nWith the goal of establishing a truly nationwide professional football league in the Philippines, the PFF launched the PFF National League Task Force on December 2, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=PFF to Establish National League in 2016|url=http://pff.org.ph/2013/12/02/pff-to-establish-national-league-in-2016/|publisher=Philippine Football Federation|accessdate=9 September 2016|date=2 December 2013}}</ref> The task force was led by Filipino economist Bernie Villegas, and is composed of UFL President Randy Roxas, AFC Deputy General Secretary and Competition Director Windsor John, Filipino FIFA official Domeka Garamendi, AFC Kick-off Program Director Yogesh Desai, UFL Commissioner Bonnie Ladrido, [[ABS-CBN]]'s Dino Laurena, former PFF' General Secretary Cyril Dofitas and Gelix Mercader.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://sg.sports.yahoo.com/blogs/thepassionatefan/pff-announces-national-football-league-launch-2015-2016-094223380.html |title=PFF announces national football league to launch in 2015 or 2016 |last=Guerrero |first=Bob |date=2 December 2013 |work=Passionate Fan |publisher=[[Yahoo! Sports]] |access-date=9 September 2016}}</ref> The task force was tasked to do market research studies to determine the possible cities or regions where participating football clubs can be based, as well as assisting clubs in the Philippines to conform to AFC club licensing regulations. The PFF initially set a goal to launch the national league in two to three years from the inception of the task force.<ref name=\"gma1\"/>\n\nSingaporean sports marketing agency, Red Card Group led by former Singaporean international, [[R. Sasikumar]], assisted the PFF in the initial stages of planning the league.<ref name=today>{{cite news|last1=Tan|first1=Noah|title=Sasikumar a key player in new Philippines pro football league|url=http://www.todayonline.com/sports/sasikumar-key-player-new-philippines-pro-football-league|accessdate=11 November 2016|work=Today|publisher=Mediacorp Press Ltd.|date=11 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Nielsen study====\n[[Nielsen Holdings PLC|Nielsen]] was tasked to conduct a study in 2015, where they identified 13 key localities throughout the Philippines as viable home venues for participating clubs in the PFL. Among the factors considered were existing infrastructures, accessibility, capacity of fans to pay, the existence of sponsors, and fan appreciation of the sport. Each applicant club was asked to nominate a home stadium based in the locality of their choosing.<ref name=\"cnnph1\"/>\n\nThe name \"Philippines Football League\" was the most-preferred name for the league in a Nielsen survey which covered interviews of 5,000 people nationwide. Other choices included P-League, Maharlika League, Liga Pilipina, and Philippine Premier League.<ref name=tv5a>{{cite news|last1=Ventura|first1=Sid|title=With PFF Backing, National Pro Football League Set to Debut in 2017|url=http://sports.tv5.com.ph/sports5/article/with-pff-backing-national-pro-football-league-set-to-debut-in-2017|accessdate=8 September 2016|work=Sports 5|publisher=TV5 Network Inc.|date=6 September 2016}}{{dead link|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Launch====\n[[File:Shangri-La Hotel, Bonifacio Global City.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Shangri-La at the Fort, Manila|Shangri-La at the Fort]] at [[Bonifacio Global City]] where the official launch of the PFL was hosted.]]\nThe Philippines Football League was officially announced on September 7, 2016 and will replace the UFL as the Philippines' top tier football league.<ref name=\"rappler1\">{{cite news|last1=Guerrero|title=PFF one step closer to launching nationwide pro football league|url=http://www.rappler.com/sports/by-sport/football/145395-pff-one-step-closer-launching-nationwide-pro-football-league|accessdate=8 September 2016|work=Rappler|date=6 September 2016}}</ref> At least six teams from all over the Philippines was planned to be part of the PFL, with clubs from the UFL invited to join. Interested clubs were presented with the PFF's Club Licensing Regulations, and were given until December 2016 to formally apply to join the PFL.<ref name=\"cnnph1\">{{cite news|last1=Del Rosario|first1=Paolo|title=PFF bares plans for national football league|url=http://cnnphilippines.com/sports/2016/09/06/PFF-bares-plans-philippines-national-football-league.html|accessdate=8 September 2016|work=CNN Philippines|date=6 September 2016}}</ref> The league competition was slated to begin in either the late March or early April in 2017.<ref name=\"ceres\"/>\n\nBy April 1, 2017, the PFF confirmed the participation of 8 clubs - [[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres\u2013Negros]], [[Davao Aguilas F.C.|Davao Aguilas]], [[Global Cebu F.C.|Global Cebu]], [[Ilocos United F.C.|Ilocos United]], [[JPV Marikina F.C.|JPV Marikina]], [[Kaya F.C.|Kaya FC\u2013Makati]], [[Loyola Meralco Sparks F.C.|Loyola Meralco Sparks]],  and [[Stallion Laguna F.C.|Stallion Laguna]].<ref name=\"kickoff8\">{{cite news|last1=Doble|first1=Henry|title=8 teams for PFL inaugural kickoff|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/bacolod/sports/2017/04/01/8-teams-pfl-inaugural-kickoff-534259|accessdate=1 April 2017|work=Sun Star Bacolod|date=1 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe official launching of the PFL happened on April 21, 2017 at the [[Shangri-La at the Fort, Manila|Shangri-La at the Fort]] in Taguig while the first match of the inaugural season is set to be played on May 6, 2017.<ref name=\"finallypfllaunch\">{{cite news|last1=Jacinto|first1=Christian|title=Finally, a national league for the Philippines after launch of PFL|url=http://www.spin.ph/football/news/finally-a-national-league-for-the-philippines-after-launch-of|accessdate=22 April 2017|work=Sport Interactive Network Philippines|date=22 April 2017}}</ref> The program was started by economist and PFL Task Force Chairman, [[Bernardo Villegas]] and ended by PFF President [[Mariano Araneta]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Inaugural PFL season draws 8 teams from Luzon, Visayas and Mindanao|url=http://www.foxsportsasia.com/en-ph/news/inaugural-pfl-season-draws-8-teams-luzon-visayas-mindanao/|accessdate=22 April 2017|work=Fox Sports Philippines|date=22 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2017 and 2018 seasons===\nThe inaugural season in 2017 was contested by eight clubs and had two stages; the regular season and the \"Final series\". The regular season adopted a home-and-away, double round-robin format. The top four teams in the regular season advanced to the play-off round dubbed as the \"Finals Series\" to determine the champions of the league.<ref name=\"Philippine Football Federation\">{{cite news|title=PFF to brief interested clubs on Philippines Football League|url=http://pff.org.ph/2016/09/06/pff-to-brief-interested-clubs-on-philippines-football-league/|accessdate=7 September 2016|publisher=Philippine Football Federation|date=6 September 2016}}</ref> A knockout cup competition will also be contested between the PFL's participating clubs, with matches interspersed within the league schedule.<ref name=\"rappler1\"/> [[Ceres-Negros F.C.|Ceres-Negros]] won the inaugural league title.\n\nFor the second season, the Final Series was scrapped due to the introduction of the [[Copa Paulino Alcantara]], the cup competition for the league.<ref name=\"pflbegins\">{{cite news|title=PFL Season 2018 Begins March 3|url=http://philippinesfootballleague.com/2018/01/31/pfl-season-2018-begins-march-3/|accessdate=31 January 2018|work=Philippines Football League|date=31 January 2018}}</ref> The number of clubs in the league was reduced from eight to six after the departure of [[Ilocos United F.C.]] and [[FC Meralco Manila]]. Ceres-Negros won their second title.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ceres captures back to back PFL titles |url=http://sports.inquirer.net/312569/ceres-captures-back-back-pfl-titles |accessdate=25 July 2018 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=25 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Replacement by the Philippine Premier League===\n{{main|Philippine Premier League}}\nIn late-2018, Triple CH led by Thailand-based Filipino businessman Bernie Sumayao became involved in the league and has entered talks with PFF chairman [[Mariano Araneta]].<ref name=\"sumayao\">{{cite news |last1=Guerrero |first1=Bob |title=Bernie Sumayao looks to transform Philippine club football |url=https://www.rappler.com/sports/by-sport/football/218516-bernie-sumayao-transform-philippine-club-football |accessdate=8 December 2018 |work=Rappler |date=8 December 2018}}</ref> He was appointed as the league's new commissioner.<ref name=\"newppl\">{{cite news |last1=Saldajeno |first1=Ivan Stewart |title=New PPL chief saddened by Davao Aguilas pullout |url=http://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1056814 |accessdate=16 December 2018 |agency=Philippine News Agency |date=16 December 2018}}</ref> Sumayao plans to institute financial and structural reforms in the league; including a rebrand of the league to the \"Philippine Premier League\" (PPL) starting the 2019 season, more favorable sponsorship policies, and the disestablishment of the franchise fee in favor of a less expensive registration fee for clubs.<ref name=\"sumayao\"/>\n\nIt was also planned that the number of clubs for the 2019 season be brought back to eight.<ref name=\"sumayao\"/> However the end of the 2017 season also saw the departure of a third club in the league's history, [[Davao Aguilas F.C.]] Despite of this, the league has received applications from new clubs aspiring to join the PFL.<ref name=\"sumayao\"/>\n\n===Revival and continued organization===\nThe PPL was effectively folded after the PFF announced its withdrawal of its sanction of the league on May 3, 2019. The PFF announced that the PPL will revert to the PFL with a new season set to begin on May 25, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Del Carmen |first1=Lorenzo |title=PFF sinks PPL, promises to revive PFL |url=https://tiebreakertimes.com.ph/tbt/pff-sinks-ppl-promises-revive-pfl/148524 |accessdate=4 May 2019 |work=Tiebreaker Times |date=4 May 2019}}</ref> The new season proceeded as planned with Ceres\u2013Negros claiming their third consecutive league title.\n\nIn November, [[Qatar Airways]] announced that it will sign a sponsorship deal with the PFL.<ref>{{cite web |title=Qatar Airways to Sponsor the Philippines Football League |url=https://www.qatarairways.com/en/press-releases/2019/November/PFL.html |publisher=Qatar Airways |accessdate=2 December 2019 |date=26 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nonong Araneta remains as PFF president |url=https://tiebreakertimes.com.ph/tbt/nonong-araneta-remains-as-pff-president/171858 |accessdate=2 December 2019 |work=Tiebreaker Times |date=29 November 2019 |quote=Qatar Airways, upon Araneta\u2019s request, has agreed to a three-year deal as title sponsor of the PFL starting next year.}}</ref> The deal was finalized on January 26, 2020 with Qatar Airways becoming the Airline partner and Title Sponsor of the PFL from 2020 until 2022.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cabanlong |first1=Xy-Zha |title=PFF-Qatar Airways seals deal for PFL Sponsorship |url=https://www.dugout.ph/pff-qatar-airways-seals-deal-for-pfl |accessdate=29 January 2020 |work=Dugout Philippines |date=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Competition format==\nThe PFL follows a traditional home-and-away double round robin format since the 2018 season.\n\nIn the inaugural season of 2017, the league had two phases, the regular season, which adopted a home-and-away, double round-robin format, and the \"Finals Series\", a play-off round where the top four teams of the regular season played each other to determine the champions of the league.<ref name=\"Philippine Football Federation\"/> A knockout cup competition will also be contested between the PFL's participating clubs, with matches interspersed within the league schedule.<ref name=\"rappler1\"/>\n\nThe league only had one division since its existence but there are plans to introduce a second division as the league expands, with a system of promotion and relegation with the PFL to be put in place.<ref name=\"rappler1\"/> The UFL has expressed its openness to serve as the second tier competition or youth league to the PFL.<ref name=\"tiebreaker\">{{cite news|last1=Valderrama|first1=Aeron Paul|title=Formation of Philippines Football League officially underway|url=http://tiebreakertimes.com/tbt/formation-philippines-football-league-officially-underway/65483|accessdate=7 September 2016|work=Tiebreaker Times|date=6 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Qualification for Asian competitions===\n*1st: Group Stage of the [[AFC Champions League]].\n\n;History of Asian qualification\n*AFC Champions League\n**2017-2020: The Champion qualifies for the Qualifying play-offs of the [[AFC Champions League]].\n**2021-Beyond: The Champion qualifies directly to the Group Stage\n*AFC Cup\n**2017: Second placers qualifies for the group stage of the [[AFC Cup]] with the third placers eligible to play in the continental cup in the event the second placers were unable to play. Starting the 2018 season, winners of the [[Copa Paulino Alcantara]] qualifies instead of the second placers in the PFL.\n**2017-2020: If Champion failed to advance in the Group stage of [[AFC Champions League]], they qualify in the Group Stage of [[AFC Cup]].\n**2021-Beyond: Winners of the [[Copa Paulino Alcantara]] qualifies for the Group Stage of [[AFC Cup]].\n\n==Clubs==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left;\n|-\n!colspan=6|Clubs as of the [[2020 Philippines Football League|2020 season]]\n|-\n\n!Team\n!City\n!Province\n!Stadium\n!Capacity\n!class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbreviation|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|[[ADT F.C.|ADT]]\n|colspan=4{{n/a}}\n|\n|-\n|[[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres\u2013Negros]]\n|[[Bacolod]]\n|[[Negros Occidental]]\n|[[Panaad Stadium]]\n|9,825\n|<ref name=\"ufldisperse\">{{cite news|last1=Biantan|first1=Jack|title=UFL teams disperse to provinces to form PH Football League|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cagayan-de-oro/sports/2016/11/24/ufl-teams-disperse-provinces-form-ph-football-league-511297|accessdate=24 November 2016|work=Sun Star Cagayan de Oro|date=24 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=ceresdenies>{{cite news|last1=Galunan|first1=Jerome|title=Ceres FC denies having 2 teams in the PFL|url=http://www.watchmendaily.com/sports/ceres-fc-denies-having-2-teams-in-the-pfl/|accessdate=1 December 2016|agency=Watchmen Daily Journal|date=28 November 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Global Makati F.C.|Global]]\n|[[Makati]]\n|N/A<br>{{small|([[Metro Manila]])}}\n|[[University of Makati Stadium]]\n|4,000\n|<ref name=\"ufldisperse\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cebu/sports/2016/12/30/limpag-global-fc-become-global-queen-city-fc-517662|title=Limpag: Global FC to become Global Queen City FC|date=2016-12-30|newspaper=Sun.Star|access-date=2017-01-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Kaya F.C.\u2013Iloilo|Kaya\u2013Iloilo]]\n|[[Iloilo City]]\n|[[Iloilo]]\n|[[Iloilo Sports Complex]]\n|7,000\n|<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ferer|first1=Cindy|title=Kaya Futbol Club chooses Iloilo as its new home court|url=http://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1024294|accessdate=6 February 2018|agency=Philippine News Agency|date=6 February 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Mendiola F.C. 1991|Mendiola 1991]]\n|[[Manila]]\n|N/A<br>{{small|([[Metro Manila]])}}\n|[[Rizal Memorial Stadium]]\n|12,873\n|\n|-\n|[[Stallion Laguna F.C.|Stallion Laguna]]\n|[[Bi\u00f1an]]\n|[[Laguna (province)|Laguna]]\n|[[Bi\u00f1an Football Stadium]]\n|2,580\n|<ref name=\"ufldisperse\"/><ref name=panaynews1>{{cite news |url=http://www.panaynews.net/stallion-jp-voltes-jump-ship-to-ph-football-league/ |title=Stallion, JP Voltes jump ship to PH Football League |first=Adrian Stewart |last=Co |publisher=Panay News |accessdate=29 December 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left;\n|-\n!colspan=7|Former clubs\n|-\n!Team\n!City\n!Province\n!Stadium\n!Capacity\n!Years active\n!class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbreviation|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|[[Davao Aguilas F.C.|Davao Aguilas]]\n|[[Tagum]]\n|[[Davao del Norte]]\n|[[Davao del Norte Sports Complex]]\n|3,000\n|2017\u20132018\n|<ref name=sunstar>{{cite news |url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cagayan-de-oro/sports/2017/02/19/biantan-davao-aguilas-vow-build-strong-team-526642/ |title=Biantan: Davao Aguilas vow to build a strong team |first=Jack |last=Biantan |publisher=SunStar |accessdate=19 February 2017 }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[F.C. Meralco Manila|Meralco Manila]]\n|[[Manila]]\n|N/A<br>{{small|([[Metro Manila]])}}\n|[[Rizal Memorial Stadium]]\n|12,873\n|2017\n|<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.football.com.ph/pff-issue-club-licenses-8-clubs-inaugural-season-philippines-football-league/ |title=PFF to Issue Club Licenses to 8 Clubs for the Inaugural Season of the Philippines Football League |publisher=football.com.ph |accessdate=5 April 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n||[[Green Archers United F.C.|Green Archers United]]\n|[[Lipa, Batangas|Lipa]]\n|[[Batangas]]\n|[[Aboitiz Pitch, Lipa|Aboitiz Pitch]]\n|1,500\n|2019\n|<ref name=\"gauprevails\">{{cite news|last1=Saldajeno|first1=Ivan Stewart|title=GAU prevails in 1st home match, pummels Air Force|url=https://www.dugout.ph/2019/08/gau-prevails-in-1st-home-match.html|accessdate=4 August 2019|work=Dugout Philippines|date=4 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=footballbatangas>{{cite news|last1=Saldajeno|first1=Ivan Stewart|title=PFL games at Aboitiz Pitch to reignite football fever in Batangas|url=https://www.dugout.ph/2019/08/reigniting-football-fever-in-batangas.html|accessdate=4 August 2019|agency=Dugout Philippines|date=4 August 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Ilocos United F.C.|Ilocos United]]\n|[[Vigan]]{{refn|The home stadium of the club is located in [[Bantay, Ilocos Sur]], a nearby town. For administrative and marketing purposes, the home city of Ilocos United is designated as \"Vigan.\"|group=\"note\"|name=\"Vigan note\"}}\n|[[Ilocos Sur]]\n|[[Quirino Stadium]]\n|5,000\n|2017\n|<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sevilla |first1=Jeremiah M. |url=http://www.manilatimes.net/ilocos-united-fc-withdraws-pfl-2018-season/375334/ |title=Ilocos United FC withdraws from PFL 2018 season|accessdate=22 February 2018 |publisher=The Manila Times|date=19 January 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Philippine Air Force F.C.|Philippine Air Force]]\n|[[Manila]]\n| N/A<br>{{small|([[Metro Manila]])}}\n| N/A\n| N/A\n|2019\n|-\n|[[JPV Marikina F.C.|JPV Marikina]]\n|[[Marikina]]\n| N/A<br>{{small|([[Metro Manila]])}}\n|[[Marikina Sports Complex]]\n| 15,000\n|2017\u20132018\n|<ref name=panaynews1/><ref name=\"nextkick\">{{cite news|last1=Tupas|first1=Cedelf|title=Football\u2019s next kick|url=http://sports.inquirer.net/235031/footballs-next-kick|accessdate=15 January 2017|publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=15 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n{{Col-2}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\" width=450px\n|-\n! colspan=5 width=500px|Locations of PFL clubs\n|-\n|align=center rowspan=2|{{location map+|Philippines|width=300|float=middle|caption=|places= {{location map~ |Philippines |lat=14.790|long= 121.145|label={{small|'''[[Metro Manila]]''' (5 clubs)}}|position=top}}\n{{Location map~ |Philippines |position=right|lat=10.640739|long=122.968956|label=[[Ceres Negros F.C.|Ceres Negros]]}}\n{{Location map~ |Philippines |position=left|lat=17.5983|long=120.4473|label=[[Ilocos United F.C.|Ilocos United]]|mark=Cyan pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~ |Philippines |position=left|lat=10.7117|long=122.5625|label=[[Kaya FC|Kaya Iloilo]]}}\n{{Location map~ |Philippines |position=left|lat=14.3036|long=121.0781|label=[[Stallion Laguna F.C.|Stallion Laguna]]}}\n{{Location map~ |Philippines |position=right|lat=14.0000|long=121.0781|label=[[Green Archers United F.C.|Green Archers United]]}}\n{{Location map~ |Philippines |position=left|lat=7.4482|long=125.8094|label=[[Davao Aguilas F.C.|Davao Aguilas]]|mark=Cyan pog.svg}}\n}}\n! width=150px|{{small|Metro Manila}}\n|-\n|{{location map+|Metro Manila|width=150|float=right|caption=|places=\n{{Location map~ |Metro Manila |position=left|lat=14.5634|long=120.992|label=[[F.C. Meralco Manila|Meralco Manila]]|mark=Cyan pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~ |Metro Manila |position=top|lat=14.6346|long=121.0984|label=[[JPV Marikina F.C.|JPV Marikina]]|mark=Cyan pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~ |Metro Manila |position=right|lat=14.6000|long=120.970|label=[[Mendiola F.C. 1991|Mendiola]]}}\n{{Location map~ |Metro Manila |position=bottom|lat=14.5160|long=121.015|label=[[Philippine Air Force F.C.|Philippine Air Force]]}}\n{{Location map~ |Metro Manila |position=right|lat=14.5634|long=121.060|label=[[Global Makati F.C.|Global Makati]]}}\n}}\n|}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==Champions==\n\n{{See also|Philippine Football League records and statistics|}}\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n;Champions\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! No.\n! Season\n! Champion\n|-\n| '''1''' || [[2017 Philippines Football League|2017]] || |[[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres-Negros]]\n|-\n| '''2''' || [[2018 Philippines Football League|2018]] || | Ceres-Negros\n|-\n| '''3''' || [[2019 Philippines Football League|2019]] || | Ceres-Negros\n|-\n|}\n{{Col-2}}\n;Wins by club\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Club\n!Wins\n!Winning years\n|-\n|{{nowrap|[[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres-Negros]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|[[2017 Philippines Football League|2017]], [[2018 Philippines Football League|2018]], [[2019 Philippines Football League|2019]]\n|-\n|}\n{{Col-2}}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n;Total titles won by region\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Region\n! Number of titles\n! Clubs\n\n|-\n| [[Negros Occidental]]\n| <center>3</center>\n| [[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres\u2013Negros]] (3)\n|-\n\n|}\n\n;By City / Town\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! City / Town\n! Championships\n! Clubs\n|-\n| [[Bacolod]]\n| <center>3</center>\n| [[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres\u2013Negros]] (3)\n|-\n\n|}\n\n==Organization==\n{{see also|Liga Futbol Inc.}}\nThe Philippines Football League, along with the PFF Cup, was managed by [[Liga Futbol Inc.]]<ref name=sportradar>{{cite news|title=Philippines Football League (PFL) partners Sportradar for multiyear data, OTT and integrity services|url=https://calvinayre.com/2018/02/22/press-releases/philippines-football-league-pfl-partners-sportradar-multiyear-data-ott-integrity-services/|accessdate=22 February 2018|work=CalvinAyre.com|date=22 February 2018}}</ref>\nSingapore-based Red Card Global, a sports marketing agency has exclusive commercial rights to the PFL.<ref name=\"asl\">{{cite news|last1=Osman|first1=Shamir|title=Phillippines &#91;sic&#93; reiterates opposition to ASL after launch of new pro league|url=http://www.tnp.sg/sports/football/phillippines-reiterates-opposition-asl-after-launch-new-pro-league|accessdate=22 April 2017|work=The New Paper|date=13 April 2017}}</ref>  Each club had to pay a franchise fee to participate in the league.<ref name=\"rappler1\"/>  Reportedly in April 2017, the franchise fee was pegged at $500,000 by the PFF which can be paid by member clubs within a period of five years.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Biantan|first1=Jack|title=Biantan: Aguilas FC lucky to have Jefferson Cheng|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cagayan-de-oro/sports/2017/04/10/biantan-aguilas-fc-lucky-have-jefferson-cheng-535895|accessdate=12 April 2017|work=Sun Star Cagayan de Oro|date=10 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe league is professional in nature and not a developmental league. The clubs are intended to have a share of the league's broadcast revenues and sponsorship and each club are to be assisted by the league in securing their own sponsors.<ref name=\"ceres\"/>\n\nThe professional status of the league is recognized by the [[Games and Amusements Board]], the regulatory body for professional sports in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite news|title=GAB grants PFL professional license|url=http://www.foxsportsasia.com/en-ph/news/gab-grants-pfl-professional-license/|accessdate=6 May 2017|work=Fox Sports Philippines|date=3 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, the [[Philippines Football Federation]] was awarded the League Development Award by the [[Asian Football Confederation]] for its organization of the PFL.<ref>{{cite web |title=Philippine FF receives League Development Award |url=http://www.the-afc.com/news/afcsection/philippine-ff-receives-league-development-award |publisher=Asian Football Confederation |accessdate=1 November 2018 |date=31 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Club identity===\nAll PFL clubs were required under the PFF Club Licensing Regulations to have a name that includes the name of their home locality. The clubs were also required to have nicknames, crests, and colors based on the unique characteristics of their home locality.<ref name=\"pffclublicensing\"/>\n\n===Players and salaries===\nParticipating clubs were allowed to have a minimum 25 and a maximum of 30 players. Reportedly in September 2016, only four foreigners are to be allowed per club, with at least one foreigner coming from an [[Asian Football Confederation|AFC]] country.<ref name=tv5a/> On January 17, 2017, it was reported that this foreign player limit rule was yet to be finalized by the PFF.<ref name=\"preparesPFL\">{{cite news|last1=Biantan|first1=Jack|title=Stallions FC Laguna prepares for Philippine Football League|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cagayan-de-oro/sports/2017/01/17/stallions-fc-laguna-prepares-philippine-football-league-520527|accessdate=17 January 2017|work=Sun Star|date=17 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe PFL reportedly planned to have a [[salary cap]] and a salary floor.<ref name=\"rappler1\"/>\n\n===Youth development===\nAll participating clubs in the PFL were required to commit to the organization and development of at least two youth teams, an under-18 and an under-15. The clubs' youth teams were required to participate in competitions organized by the Philippine Football Federation.<ref name=\"pffclublicensing\">{{cite web|title=Club Licensing Regulations for Philippines Football League|url=http://pff.org.ph/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/PFL-Club-Licesing-2016.pdf|publisher=Philippine Football Federation|accessdate=7 September 2016|location=Pasig|date=23 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Stadiums===\nThe clubs of the PFL were required to have a certified home stadium either through ownership of the stadium or having an active contract with the owners of the stadium. Likewise, all clubs were required to have access to or own a training field and facility.<ref name=\"pffclublicensing\"/>\n\n==Media coverage==\n[[File:Ceres vs Kaya PFL prematch con May 11 2018.jpg|thumb|alt=Arnie Pasinabo of Ceres-Negros (2nd from left) shakes the hand of Jalsor Soriano of Kaya FC-Iloilo in a press conference. They are flanked by the head coaches of their clubs|Press conference held prior to a league match between Ceres-Negros and Kaya-Iloilo. May 11, 2018.]]\nThe Philippine Football Federation had an agreement with the [[People's Television Network]] to broadcast matches of the league which was signed in April 2017<ref name=ptv>{{cite AV media | people= | date=12 April 2017 | title=PTV Network at PFF, pumirma ng kasunduan | trans-title = PTV Network and the PFF signed an agreement |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5bibJhoaZEA | medium= Television production | location= | publisher=People's Television Network}}</ref> though the network coverage of the league didn't last at least half a season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Limpag|first1=Mike|title=Here\u2019s hoping to a better PFL in 2018|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cebu/sports/2017/12/29/limpag-heres-hoping-better-pfl-2018-581596|accessdate=2 January 2018|work=Sun Star Cebu|date=28 December 2017}}</ref> Matches since then were live streamed through the MyCujoo online platform.<ref>{{cite news|last1=del Carmen|first1=Lorenzo|title=Smart Sports\u2019 Best of 2017: Banner year for Filipinas, Ceres-Negros|url=http://tiebreakertimes.com.ph/tbt/smart-sports-best-2017-football-banner-year-filipinas-ceres-negros/104879|accessdate=2 January 2018|work=Tiebreaker Times|date=1 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn February 22, 2018, the league had signed an agreement with [[Sportradar]] which would enable it livestream matches through Sportradar's Over-The-Top (OTT) platform.<ref name=sportradar/><ref>{{cite news|last1=del Carmen|first1=Lorenzo|title=PFL, Sportradar sign deal for online broadcast platform|url=https://tiebreakertimes.com.ph/tbt/pfl-sportradar-sign-deal-online-broadcast-platform/109846|accessdate=22 February 2018|work=Tiebreaker Times|date=22 February 2018}}</ref> In April 2018, Liga Futbol Inc. approved a budget to secure a broadcasting partner for the 2018 season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Doble|first1=Henry|title=PFL soon to air live coverage|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/bacolod/sports/2018/04/04/pfl-soon-air-live-coverage-596718|accessdate=4 April 2018|work=Sun Star Bacolod|date=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2019 season, all matches were streamed on Facebook and the league's official website.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Saldajeno |first1=Ivan Stewart |title=Qatar Airways formalizes partnership with PFL |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1092372 |accessdate=31 January 2020 |agency=Philippine News Agency |date=29 January 2020 |quote=The PFL did not enjoy having televised matches all season long last year from the league season to the Copa Paulino Alcantara, although all of the matches were streamed live in the PFL website and in its Facebook page.}}</ref>\n\nThe Qatar Airways sponsorship deal signed with the league in January 2020 includes provisions to broadcast select matches live on television.<ref name=\"pffqatar\">{{cite news |title=PFF Inks Three-Year Partnership With Qatar Airways For The PFL |url=http://pff.org.ph/2020/01/29/pff-inks-three-year-partnership-with-qatar-airways-for-the-pfl/ |accessdate=29 January 2020 |publisher=Philippine Football Federation |date=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Philippines Football League}}\n{{2018 in Philippine football}}\n{{Football in the Philippines}}\n{{Sports leagues in the Philippines}}\n{{Metro Manila Sports}}\n{{AFC leagues}}\n\n[[Category:Top level football leagues in Asia|Philippines]]\n[[Category:Sports leagues established in 2017]]\n[[Category:Football leagues in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Philippines Football League| ]]\n[[Category:Professional sports leagues in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:2017 establishments in the Philippines]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Top-level association football league in the Philippines}}\n{{Infobox football league\n|image = Philippines Football League Logo.png\n|image_size = 200px\n|country = Philippines\n|organiser = [[Liga Futbol Inc.]]\n|confed = [[Asian Football Confederation|AFC]] \n|founded = 2017\n|folded =\n|teams = 6\n|relegation =\n|level = 1\n|domest_cup = [[Copa Paulino Alcantara]]\n|confed_cup = [[AFC Champions League]] <br> [[AFC Cup]] \n|champions = [[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres\u2013Negros]] (3rd title)\n|season = [[2019 Philippines Football League|2019]]\n|most successful club = [[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres\u2013Negros]] (3 titles)\n|top_goalscorer = [[Bienvenido Mara\u00f1\u00f3n]] (67)<!--as of the end of the 2019 season -->\n|tv = \n|website = {{URL|www.pfl.org.ph}}\n|current = [[2020 Philippines Football League]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Philippines Football League''', commonly known as '''PFL''', is a Filipino professional [[association football]] league sanctioned by the [[Philippine Football Federation]] (PFF). It is the [[Philippines|Philippines']] highest level of men's club football, surpassing the [[United Football League (Philippines)|United Football League]] (UFL), which was previously the ''de facto'' top-tier league in the country.<ref name=\"ceres\">{{cite news|title=Ceres FC ready to apply for PFL license|url=http://visayandailystar.com/2016/October/15/sportnews1.htm|accessdate=16 October 2016|work=The Visayan Daily Star|date=15 October 2016}}</ref> Starting from the 2020 season, the league is also known as '''The Philippines Football League brought to you by Qatar Airways<ref>https://www.facebook.com/pg/PhilippinesFootballLeagueOfficial/about/</ref>''' due to the league's title sponsorship of [[Qatar Airways]]\n\nThe PFL followed a home-and-away format as opposed to the UFL, and has had three seasons thus far ([[2017 Philippines Football League|2017]], [[2018 Philippines Football League|2018]], [[2019 Philippines Football League|2019]]), which were all won by [[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres\u2013Negros]]. In 2018, financial and logistical issues forced the disestablishment of the PFL with the [[Philippine Premier League]] established in its place. However, with the folding of the PPL after just one match day, the PFL was revived in mid-May 2019.\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\nFollowing the success of the [[Philippines national football team|Philippines national team]] in the [[2010 AFF Championship|2010 AFF Suzuki Cup]], Philippine football experienced a renaissance. With no existing national football league, the [[Metro Manila]]-based [[United Football League (Philippines)|United Football League]] (UFL) became the ''de facto'' top-tier league in the Philippines. Under the guidance of the Football Alliance (FA) in partnership with United Football Clubs Association (UFCA), the UFL flourished. However, the PFF expressed the need to have a nationwide, community-based football league that is at par with the standards set by the [[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] (FIFA) and the [[Asian Football Confederation]] (AFC).<ref name=\"gma1\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/337938/sports/football/philippine-football-federation-set-to-launch-national-league |title=Philippine Football Federation set to launch national league |last=Bautista |first=Roehl Ni\u00f1o |date=2 December 2013 |work=[[GMA News]] |access-date=8 September 2016}}</ref> The UFL, which is under the [[National Capital Region F.A.|National Capital Region Football Association]], cannot be considered as a national league.\n\n===Foundations===\n[[File:PFL Philippines Nielsen Study Cited Localities map.svg|250px|thumb|alt=Map showing the 13 localities (provinces, cities or municipalities) in red deemed viable home venues for prospect clubs of the Philippines Football League|13 localities deemed viable home venues by the Nielsen Company for prospect clubs in the PFL.<ref name=\"cnnph1\"/>\n{{smalldiv|\n{{unbulleted list|'''[[Luzon]]''': [[Manila]], [[Makati]], [[Quezon City]], [[Marikina]], [[Bocaue, Bulacan|Bocaue]] ([[Bulacan]]), [[Laguna (province)|Laguna]], [[Pampanga]]|'''[[Visayas]]''': [[Cebu]], [[Bacolod]], [[Iloilo]]|'''[[Mindanao]]''': [[Davao City]], [[Cagayan de Oro]], [[Zamboanga City]]}}}}\n]]\nWith the goal of establishing a truly nationwide professional football league in the Philippines, the PFF launched the PFF National League Task Force on December 2, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=PFF to Establish National League in 2016|url=http://pff.org.ph/2013/12/02/pff-to-establish-national-league-in-2016/|publisher=Philippine Football Federation|accessdate=9 September 2016|date=2 December 2013}}</ref> The task force was led by Filipino economist Bernie Villegas, and is composed of UFL President Randy Roxas, AFC Deputy General Secretary and Competition Director Windsor John, Filipino FIFA official Domeka Garamendi, AFC Kick-off Program Director Yogesh Desai, UFL Commissioner Bonnie Ladrido, [[ABS-CBN]]'s Dino Laurena, former PFF' General Secretary Cyril Dofitas and Gelix Mercader.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://sg.sports.yahoo.com/blogs/thepassionatefan/pff-announces-national-football-league-launch-2015-2016-094223380.html |title=PFF announces national football league to launch in 2015 or 2016 |last=Guerrero |first=Bob |date=2 December 2013 |work=Passionate Fan |publisher=[[Yahoo! Sports]] |access-date=9 September 2016}}</ref> The task force was tasked to do market research studies to determine the possible cities or regions where participating football clubs can be based, as well as assisting clubs in the Philippines to conform to AFC club licensing regulations. The PFF initially set a goal to launch the national league in two to three years from the inception of the task force.<ref name=\"gma1\"/>\n\nSingaporean sports marketing agency, Red Card Group led by former Singaporean international, [[R. Sasikumar]], assisted the PFF in the initial stages of planning the league.<ref name=today>{{cite news|last1=Tan|first1=Noah|title=Sasikumar a key player in new Philippines pro football league|url=http://www.todayonline.com/sports/sasikumar-key-player-new-philippines-pro-football-league|accessdate=11 November 2016|work=Today|publisher=Mediacorp Press Ltd.|date=11 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Nielsen study====\n[[Nielsen Holdings PLC|Nielsen]] was tasked to conduct a study in 2015, where they identified 13 key localities throughout the Philippines as viable home venues for participating clubs in the PFL. Among the factors considered were existing infrastructures, accessibility, capacity of fans to pay, the existence of sponsors, and fan appreciation of the sport. Each applicant club was asked to nominate a home stadium based in the locality of their choosing.<ref name=\"cnnph1\"/>\n\nThe name \"Philippines Football League\" was the most-preferred name for the league in a Nielsen survey which covered interviews of 5,000 people nationwide. Other choices included P-League, Maharlika League, Liga Pilipina, and Philippine Premier League.<ref name=tv5a>{{cite news|last1=Ventura|first1=Sid|title=With PFF Backing, National Pro Football League Set to Debut in 2017|url=http://sports.tv5.com.ph/sports5/article/with-pff-backing-national-pro-football-league-set-to-debut-in-2017|accessdate=8 September 2016|work=Sports 5|publisher=TV5 Network Inc.|date=6 September 2016}}{{dead link|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Launch====\n[[File:Shangri-La Hotel, Bonifacio Global City.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Shangri-La at the Fort, Manila|Shangri-La at the Fort]] at [[Bonifacio Global City]] where the official launch of the PFL was hosted.]]\nThe Philippines Football League was officially announced on September 7, 2016 and will replace the UFL as the Philippines' top tier football league.<ref name=\"rappler1\">{{cite news|last1=Guerrero|title=PFF one step closer to launching nationwide pro football league|url=http://www.rappler.com/sports/by-sport/football/145395-pff-one-step-closer-launching-nationwide-pro-football-league|accessdate=8 September 2016|work=Rappler|date=6 September 2016}}</ref> At least six teams from all over the Philippines was planned to be part of the PFL, with clubs from the UFL invited to join. Interested clubs were presented with the PFF's Club Licensing Regulations, and were given until December 2016 to formally apply to join the PFL.<ref name=\"cnnph1\">{{cite news|last1=Del Rosario|first1=Paolo|title=PFF bares plans for national football league|url=http://cnnphilippines.com/sports/2016/09/06/PFF-bares-plans-philippines-national-football-league.html|accessdate=8 September 2016|work=CNN Philippines|date=6 September 2016}}</ref> The league competition was slated to begin in either the late March or early April in 2017.<ref name=\"ceres\"/>\n\nBy April 1, 2017, the PFF confirmed the participation of 8 clubs - [[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres\u2013Negros]], [[Davao Aguilas F.C.|Davao Aguilas]], [[Global Cebu F.C.|Global Cebu]], [[Ilocos United F.C.|Ilocos United]], [[JPV Marikina F.C.|JPV Marikina]], [[Kaya F.C.|Kaya FC\u2013Makati]], [[Loyola Meralco Sparks F.C.|Loyola Meralco Sparks]],  and [[Stallion Laguna F.C.|Stallion Laguna]].<ref name=\"kickoff8\">{{cite news|last1=Doble|first1=Henry|title=8 teams for PFL inaugural kickoff|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/bacolod/sports/2017/04/01/8-teams-pfl-inaugural-kickoff-534259|accessdate=1 April 2017|work=Sun Star Bacolod|date=1 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe official launching of the PFL happened on April 21, 2017 at the [[Shangri-La at the Fort, Manila|Shangri-La at the Fort]] in Taguig while the first match of the inaugural season is set to be played on May 6, 2017.<ref name=\"finallypfllaunch\">{{cite news|last1=Jacinto|first1=Christian|title=Finally, a national league for the Philippines after launch of PFL|url=http://www.spin.ph/football/news/finally-a-national-league-for-the-philippines-after-launch-of|accessdate=22 April 2017|work=Sport Interactive Network Philippines|date=22 April 2017}}</ref> The program was started by economist and PFL Task Force Chairman, [[Bernardo Villegas]] and ended by PFF President [[Mariano Araneta]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Inaugural PFL season draws 8 teams from Luzon, Visayas and Mindanao|url=http://www.foxsportsasia.com/en-ph/news/inaugural-pfl-season-draws-8-teams-luzon-visayas-mindanao/|accessdate=22 April 2017|work=Fox Sports Philippines|date=22 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2017 and 2018 seasons===\nThe inaugural season in 2017 was participated by eight clubs and had two stages; the regular season and the \"Final series\". The regular season adopted a home-and-away, double round-robin format. The top four teams in the regular season advanced to the play-off round dubbed as the \"Finals Series\" to determine the champions of the league.<ref name=\"Philippine Football Federation\">{{cite news|title=PFF to brief interested clubs on Philippines Football League|url=http://pff.org.ph/2016/09/06/pff-to-brief-interested-clubs-on-philippines-football-league/|accessdate=7 September 2016|publisher=Philippine Football Federation|date=6 September 2016}}</ref> A knockout cup competition will also be contested between the PFL's participating clubs, with matches interspersed within the league schedule.<ref name=\"rappler1\"/> [[Ceres-Negros F.C.|Ceres-Negros]] won the inaugural league title.\n\nFor the second season, the Final Series was scrapped due to the introduction of the [[Copa Paulino Alcantara]], the cup competition for the league.<ref name=\"pflbegins\">{{cite news|title=PFL Season 2018 Begins March 3|url=http://philippinesfootballleague.com/2018/01/31/pfl-season-2018-begins-march-3/|accessdate=31 January 2018|work=Philippines Football League|date=31 January 2018}}</ref> The number of clubs in the league was reduced from eight to six after the departure of [[Ilocos United F.C.]] and [[FC Meralco Manila]]. Ceres-Negros won their second title.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ceres captures back to back PFL titles |url=http://sports.inquirer.net/312569/ceres-captures-back-back-pfl-titles |accessdate=25 July 2018 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=25 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Replacement by the Philippine Premier League===\n{{main|Philippine Premier League}}\nIn late-2018, Triple CH led by Thailand-based Filipino businessman Bernie Sumayao became involved in the league and has entered talks with PFF chairman [[Mariano Araneta]].<ref name=\"sumayao\">{{cite news |last1=Guerrero |first1=Bob |title=Bernie Sumayao looks to transform Philippine club football |url=https://www.rappler.com/sports/by-sport/football/218516-bernie-sumayao-transform-philippine-club-football |accessdate=8 December 2018 |work=Rappler |date=8 December 2018}}</ref> He was appointed as the league's new commissioner.<ref name=\"newppl\">{{cite news |last1=Saldajeno |first1=Ivan Stewart |title=New PPL chief saddened by Davao Aguilas pullout |url=http://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1056814 |accessdate=16 December 2018 |agency=Philippine News Agency |date=16 December 2018}}</ref> Sumayao plans to institute financial and structural reforms in the league; including a rebrand of the league to the \"Philippine Premier League\" (PPL) starting the 2019 season, more favorable sponsorship policies, and the disestablishment of the franchise fee in favor of a less expensive registration fee for clubs.<ref name=\"sumayao\"/>\n\nIt was also planned that the number of clubs for the 2019 season be brought back to eight.<ref name=\"sumayao\"/> However the end of the 2017 season also saw the departure of a third club in the league's history, [[Davao Aguilas F.C.]] Despite of this, the league has received applications from new clubs aspiring to join the PFL.<ref name=\"sumayao\"/>\n\n===Revival and continued organization===\nThe PPL was effectively folded after the PFF announced its withdrawal of its sanction of the league on May 3, 2019. The PFF announced that the PPL will revert to the PFL with a new season set to begin on May 25, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Del Carmen |first1=Lorenzo |title=PFF sinks PPL, promises to revive PFL |url=https://tiebreakertimes.com.ph/tbt/pff-sinks-ppl-promises-revive-pfl/148524 |accessdate=4 May 2019 |work=Tiebreaker Times |date=4 May 2019}}</ref> The new season proceeded as planned with Ceres\u2013Negros claiming their third consecutive league title.\n\nIn November, [[Qatar Airways]] announced that it will sign a sponsorship deal with the PFL.<ref>{{cite web |title=Qatar Airways to Sponsor the Philippines Football League |url=https://www.qatarairways.com/en/press-releases/2019/November/PFL.html |publisher=Qatar Airways |accessdate=2 December 2019 |date=26 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nonong Araneta remains as PFF president |url=https://tiebreakertimes.com.ph/tbt/nonong-araneta-remains-as-pff-president/171858 |accessdate=2 December 2019 |work=Tiebreaker Times |date=29 November 2019 |quote=Qatar Airways, upon Araneta\u2019s request, has agreed to a three-year deal as title sponsor of the PFL starting next year.}}</ref> The deal was finalized on January 26, 2020 with Qatar Airways becoming the Airline partner and Title Sponsor of the PFL from 2020 until 2022.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cabanlong |first1=Xy-Zha |title=PFF-Qatar Airways seals deal for PFL Sponsorship |url=https://www.dugout.ph/pff-qatar-airways-seals-deal-for-pfl |accessdate=29 January 2020 |work=Dugout Philippines |date=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Competition format==\nThe PFL follows a traditional home-and-away double round robin format since the 2018 season.\n\nIn the inaugural season of 2017, the league had two phases, the regular season, which adopted a home-and-away, double round-robin format, and the \"Finals Series\", a play-off round where the top four teams of the regular season played each other to determine the champions of the league.<ref name=\"Philippine Football Federation\"/> A knockout cup competition will also be contested between the PFL's participating clubs, with matches interspersed within the league schedule.<ref name=\"rappler1\"/>\n\nThe league only had one division since its existence but there are plans to introduce a second division as the league expands, with a system of promotion and relegation with the PFL to be put in place.<ref name=\"rappler1\"/> The UFL has expressed its openness to serve as the second tier competition or youth league to the PFL.<ref name=\"tiebreaker\">{{cite news|last1=Valderrama|first1=Aeron Paul|title=Formation of Philippines Football League officially underway|url=http://tiebreakertimes.com/tbt/formation-philippines-football-league-officially-underway/65483|accessdate=7 September 2016|work=Tiebreaker Times|date=6 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Qualification for Asian competitions===\n*1st: Group Stage of the [[AFC Champions League]].\n\n;History of Asian qualification\n*AFC Champions League\n**2017-2020: The Champion qualifies for the Qualifying play-offs of the [[AFC Champions League]].\n**2021-Beyond: The Champion qualifies directly to the Group Stage\n\n*AFC Cup\n**2017: Second placers qualifies for the group stage of the [[AFC Cup]] with the third placers eligible to play in the continental cup in the event the second placers were unable to play. Starting the 2018 season, winners of the [[Copa Paulino Alcantara]] qualifies instead of the second placers in the PFL.\n**2017-2020: If Champion failed to advance in the Group stage of [[AFC Champions League]], they qualify in the Group Stage of [[AFC Cup]].\n**2021-Beyond: Winners of the [[Copa Paulino Alcantara]] qualifies for the Group Stage of [[AFC Cup]].\n\n==Clubs==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left;\n|-\n!colspan=6|Clubs as of the [[2020 Philippines Football League|2020 season]]\n|-\n\n!Team\n!City\n!Province\n!Stadium\n!Capacity\n!class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbreviation|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|[[ADT F.C.|ADT]]\n|colspan=4{{n/a}}\n|\n|-\n|[[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres\u2013Negros]]\n|[[Bacolod]]\n|[[Negros Occidental]]\n|[[Panaad Stadium]]\n|9,825\n|<ref name=\"ufldisperse\">{{cite news|last1=Biantan|first1=Jack|title=UFL teams disperse to provinces to form PH Football League|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cagayan-de-oro/sports/2016/11/24/ufl-teams-disperse-provinces-form-ph-football-league-511297|accessdate=24 November 2016|work=Sun Star Cagayan de Oro|date=24 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=ceresdenies>{{cite news|last1=Galunan|first1=Jerome|title=Ceres FC denies having 2 teams in the PFL|url=http://www.watchmendaily.com/sports/ceres-fc-denies-having-2-teams-in-the-pfl/|accessdate=1 December 2016|agency=Watchmen Daily Journal|date=28 November 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Global Makati F.C.|Global]]\n|[[Makati]]\n|N/A<br>{{small|([[Metro Manila]])}}\n|[[University of Makati Stadium]]\n|4,000\n|<ref name=\"ufldisperse\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cebu/sports/2016/12/30/limpag-global-fc-become-global-queen-city-fc-517662|title=Limpag: Global FC to become Global Queen City FC|date=2016-12-30|newspaper=Sun.Star|access-date=2017-01-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Kaya F.C.\u2013Iloilo|Kaya\u2013Iloilo]]\n|[[Iloilo City]]\n|[[Iloilo]]\n|[[Iloilo Sports Complex]]\n|7,000\n|<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ferer|first1=Cindy|title=Kaya Futbol Club chooses Iloilo as its new home court|url=http://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1024294|accessdate=6 February 2