t=10.640739|long=122.968956|label=[[Ceres Negros F.C.|Ceres Negros]]}}\n{{Location map~ |Philippines |position=left|lat=17.5983|long=120.4473|label=[[Ilocos United F.C.|Ilocos United]]|mark=Cyan pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~ |Philippines |position=left|lat=10.7117|long=122.5625|label=[[Kaya FC|Kaya Iloilo]]}}\n{{Location map~ |Philippines |position=left|lat=14.3036|long=121.0781|label=[[Stallion Laguna F.C.|Stallion Laguna]]}}\n{{Location map~ |Philippines |position=right|lat=14.0000|long=121.0781|label=[[Green Archers United F.C.|Green Archers United]]}}\n{{Location map~ |Philippines |position=left|lat=7.4482|long=125.8094|label=[[Davao Aguilas F.C.|Davao Aguilas]]|mark=Cyan pog.svg}}\n}}\n! width=150px|{{small|Metro Manila}}\n|-\n|{{location map+|Metro Manila|width=150|float=right|caption=|places=\n{{Location map~ |Metro Manila |position=left|lat=14.5634|long=120.992|label=[[F.C. Meralco Manila|Meralco Manila]]|mark=Cyan pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~ |Metro Manila |position=top|lat=14.6346|long=121.0984|label=[[JPV Marikina F.C.|JPV Marikina]]|mark=Cyan pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~ |Metro Manila |position=right|lat=14.6000|long=120.970|label=[[Mendiola F.C. 1991|Mendiola]]}}\n{{Location map~ |Metro Manila |position=bottom|lat=14.5160|long=121.015|label=[[Philippine Air Force F.C.|Philippine Air Force]]}}\n{{Location map~ |Metro Manila |position=right|lat=14.5634|long=121.060|label=[[Global Makati F.C.|Global Makati]]}}\n}}\n|}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==Champions==\n\n{{See also|Philippine Football League records and statistics|}}\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n;Champions\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! No.\n! Season\n! Champion\n|-\n| '''1''' || [[2017 Philippines Football League|2017]] || |[[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres-Negros]]\n|-\n| '''2''' || [[2018 Philippines Football League|2018]] || | Ceres-Negros\n|-\n| '''3''' || [[2019 Philippines Football League|2019]] || | Ceres-Negros\n|-\n|}\n{{Col-2}}\n;Wins by club\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Club\n!Wins\n!Winning years\n|-\n|{{nowrap|[[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres-Negros]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|[[2017 Philippines Football League|2017]], [[2018 Philippines Football League|2018]], [[2019 Philippines Football League|2019]]\n|-\n|}\n{{Col-2}}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n;Total titles won by region\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Region\n! Number of titles\n! Clubs\n\n|-\n| [[Negros Occidental]]\n| <center>3</center>\n| [[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres\u2013Negros]] (3)\n|-\n\n|}\n\n;By City / Town\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! City / Town\n! Championships\n! Clubs\n|-\n| [[Bacolod]]\n| <center>3</center>\n| [[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres\u2013Negros]] (3)\n|-\n\n|}\n\n==Organization==\n{{see also|Liga Futbol Inc.}}\nThe Philippines Football League, along with the PFF Cup, was managed by [[Liga Futbol Inc.]]<ref name=sportradar>{{cite news|title=Philippines Football League (PFL) partners Sportradar for multiyear data, OTT and integrity services|url=https://calvinayre.com/2018/02/22/press-releases/philippines-football-league-pfl-partners-sportradar-multiyear-data-ott-integrity-services/|accessdate=22 February 2018|work=CalvinAyre.com|date=22 February 2018}}</ref>\nSingapore-based Red Card Global, a sports marketing agency has exclusive commercial rights to the PFL.<ref name=\"asl\">{{cite news|last1=Osman|first1=Shamir|title=Phillippines &#91;sic&#93; reiterates opposition to ASL after launch of new pro league|url=http://www.tnp.sg/sports/football/phillippines-reiterates-opposition-asl-after-launch-new-pro-league|accessdate=22 April 2017|work=The New Paper|date=13 April 2017}}</ref>  Each club had to pay a franchise fee to participate in the league.<ref name=\"rappler1\"/>  Reportedly in April 2017, the franchise fee was pegged at $500,000 by the PFF which can be paid by member clubs within a period of five years.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Biantan|first1=Jack|title=Biantan: Aguilas FC lucky to have Jefferson Cheng|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cagayan-de-oro/sports/2017/04/10/biantan-aguilas-fc-lucky-have-jefferson-cheng-535895|accessdate=12 April 2017|work=Sun Star Cagayan de Oro|date=10 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe league is professional in nature and not a developmental league. The clubs are intended to have a share of the league's broadcast revenues and sponsorship and each club are to be assisted by the league in securing their own sponsors.<ref name=\"ceres\"/>\n\nThe professional status of the league is recognized by the [[Games and Amusements Board]], the regulatory body for professional sports in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite news|title=GAB grants PFL professional license|url=http://www.foxsportsasia.com/en-ph/news/gab-grants-pfl-professional-license/|accessdate=6 May 2017|work=Fox Sports Philippines|date=3 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, the [[Philippines Football Federation]] was awarded the League Development Award by the [[Asian Football Confederation]] for its organization of the PFL.<ref>{{cite web |title=Philippine FF receives League Development Award |url=http://www.the-afc.com/news/afcsection/philippine-ff-receives-league-development-award |publisher=Asian Football Confederation |accessdate=1 November 2018 |date=31 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Club identity===\nAll PFL clubs were required under the PFF Club Licensing Regulations to have a name that includes the name of their home locality. The clubs were also required to have nicknames, crests, and colors based on the unique characteristics of their home locality.<ref name=\"pffclublicensing\"/>\n\n===Players and salaries===\nParticipating clubs were allowed to have a minimum 25 and a maximum of 30 players. Reportedly in September 2016, only four foreigners are to be allowed per club, with at least one foreigner coming from an [[Asian Football Confederation|AFC]] country.<ref name=tv5a/> On January 17, 2017, it was reported that this foreign player limit rule was yet to be finalized by the PFF.<ref name=\"preparesPFL\">{{cite news|last1=Biantan|first1=Jack|title=Stallions FC Laguna prepares for Philippine Football League|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cagayan-de-oro/sports/2017/01/17/stallions-fc-laguna-prepares-philippine-football-league-520527|accessdate=17 January 2017|work=Sun Star|date=17 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe PFL reportedly planned to have a [[salary cap]] and a salary floor.<ref name=\"rappler1\"/>\n\n===Youth development===\nAll participating clubs in the PFL were required to commit to the organization and development of at least two youth teams, an under-18 and an under-15. The clubs' youth teams were required to participate in competitions organized by the Philippine Football Federation.<ref name=\"pffclublicensing\">{{cite web|title=Club Licensing Regulations for Philippines Football League|url=http://pff.org.ph/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/PFL-Club-Licesing-2016.pdf|publisher=Philippine Football Federation|accessdate=7 September 2016|location=Pasig|date=23 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Stadiums===\nThe clubs of the PFL were required to have a certified home stadium either through ownership of the stadium or having an active contract with the owners of the stadium. Likewise, all clubs were required to have access to or own a training field and facility.<ref name=\"pffclublicensing\"/>\n\n==Media coverage==\n[[File:Ceres vs Kaya PFL prematch con May 11 2018.jpg|thumb|alt=Arnie Pasinabo of Ceres-Negros (2nd from left) shakes the hand of Jalsor Soriano of Kaya FC-Iloilo in a press conference. They are flanked by the head coaches of their clubs|Press conference held prior to a league match between Ceres-Negros and Kaya-Iloilo. May 11, 2018.]]\nThe Philippine Football Federation had an agreement with the [[People's Television Network]] to broadcast matches of the league which was signed in April 2017<ref name=ptv>{{cite AV media | people= | date=12 April 2017 | title=PTV Network at PFF, pumirma ng kasunduan | trans-title = PTV Network and the PFF signed an agreement |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5bibJhoaZEA | medium= Television production | location= | publisher=People's Television Network}}</ref> though the network coverage of the league didn't last at least half a season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Limpag|first1=Mike|title=Here\u2019s hoping to a better PFL in 2018|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cebu/sports/2017/12/29/limpag-heres-hoping-better-pfl-2018-581596|accessdate=2 January 2018|work=Sun Star Cebu|date=28 December 2017}}</ref> Matches since then were live streamed through the MyCujoo online platform.<ref>{{cite news|last1=del Carmen|first1=Lorenzo|title=Smart Sports\u2019 Best of 2017: Banner year for Filipinas, Ceres-Negros|url=http://tiebreakertimes.com.ph/tbt/smart-sports-best-2017-football-banner-year-filipinas-ceres-negros/104879|accessdate=2 January 2018|work=Tiebreaker Times|date=1 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn February 22, 2018, the league had signed an agreement with [[Sportradar]] which would enable it livestream matches through Sportradar's Over-The-Top (OTT) platform.<ref name=sportradar/><ref>{{cite news|last1=del Carmen|first1=Lorenzo|title=PFL, Sportradar sign deal for online broadcast platform|url=https://tiebreakertimes.com.ph/tbt/pfl-sportradar-sign-deal-online-broadcast-platform/109846|accessdate=22 February 2018|work=Tiebreaker Times|date=22 February 2018}}</ref> In April 2018, Liga Futbol Inc. approved a budget to secure a broadcasting partner for the 2018 season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Doble|first1=Henry|title=PFL soon to air live coverage|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/bacolod/sports/2018/04/04/pfl-soon-air-live-coverage-596718|accessdate=4 April 2018|work=Sun Star Bacolod|date=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2019 season, all matches were streamed on Facebook and the league's official website.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Saldajeno |first1=Ivan Stewart |title=Qatar Airways formalizes partnership with PFL |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1092372 |accessdate=31 January 2020 |agency=Philippine News Agency |date=29 January 2020 |quote=The PFL did not enjoy having televised matches all season long last year from the league season to the Copa Paulino Alcantara, although all of the matches were streamed live in the PFL website and in its Facebook page.}}</ref>\n\nThe Qatar Airways sponsorship deal signed with the league in January 2020 includes provisions to broadcast select matches live on television.<ref name=\"pffqatar\">{{cite news |title=PFF Inks Three-Year Partnership With Qatar Airways For The PFL |url=http://pff.org.ph/2020/01/29/pff-inks-three-year-partnership-with-qatar-airways-for-the-pfl/ |accessdate=29 January 2020 |publisher=Philippine Football Federation |date=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Philippines Football League}}\n{{2018 in Philippine football}}\n{{Football in the Philippines}}\n{{Sports leagues in the Philippines}}\n{{Metro Manila Sports}}\n{{AFC leagues}}\n\n[[Category:Top level football leagues in Asia|Philippines]]\n[[Category:Sports leagues established in 2017]]\n[[Category:Football leagues in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Philippines Football League| ]]\n[[Category:Professional sports leagues in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:2017 establishments in the Philippines]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar/generalfixes, replaced: was participated by \u2192 was contested by", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philippines_Football_League"}
